    {
      "id": 295,
      "name": "Command Monster",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Enchantment",
      "caster": "priest",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": false,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "60 yds.",
      "aoe": "1 creature",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "1 rd./2 levels",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** allows the priest to issue a command to any one creature within the spell's range.\n\nThe magic of the spell translates the priest's order into a language or form the subject creature can understand.\n\nThe creature must have an Intelligence of at least 1 in order to be affected by this spell; nonintelligent creatures (those with a score of 0) cannot comprehend any order, no matter how the priest phrases it.\n\nOther creatures gain a saving throw vs.\n\nspell to resist command monster, but only if they have an Intelligence of Exceptional (15) or better, or the creature's levels or Hit Dice are equal to or greater than the caster's.\n\nJust like the 1st-level spell command, this spell coerces the subject into obeying the priest's one-word order to the best of its ability.\n\nThe order must be absolutely clear and unequivocal; the subject will continue to obey for one round per two caster levels- six rounds at 12th level, seven at 14th, and so on.\n\nIf this action places the subject in mortal peril, he may attempt a saving throw (whether he was originally entitled to one or not) in order to break free of the spell's power.\n\nTherefore, ordering a character standing at the edge of a cliff to \"jump\" will create an opportunity for the subject to break free.\n\nA command to \"die\" or \"sleep\" renders the creature unconscious for the spell's duration.\n\nUndead creatures are immune to this spell.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 176,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 296,
      "name": "Conjure Animals",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Conjuration",
      "caster": "priest",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "30 yds.",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "9",
      "duration": "2 rds./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "The conjure animals spell enables the priest to magically create one or more mammals to attack his opponents.\n\nThe total Hit Dice of the mammals cannot exceed twice his level, if the creature conjured is determined randomly.\n\nIf a specific animal type is requested, the animal's Hit Dice cannot exceed his level.\n\nThe DM selects the type of animal that appears if it is randomly called.\n\nThus, a priest of 12th level could randomly conjure two mammals with 12 Hit Dice each, four with 6 Hit Dice each, six with 4 Hit Dice each, eight with 3 Hit Dice each, 12 with 2 Hit Dice each, or 24 with 1 Hit Die each.\n\nCount every +1 hit point added to a creature's Hit Dice as _ of a Hit Die.\n\nThus a creature with 4 + 3 Hit Dice equals a 4 _ Hit Dice creature.\n\nThe conjured animals remain for two rounds for conjured animals remain for two rounds for each level of the conjuring priest, or until slain, and they follow the caster's verbal commands.\n\nConjured animals unfailingly attack the priest's opponents, but resist being used for any other purpose--they do not like it, become noticeably more difficult to control, and may refuse any action, break free, or turn on the caster, depending on the nature of the creature and the details of the situation.\n\nThe conjured animals disappear when slain.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 288,
      "reversible": false
