    {
      "id": 373,
      "name": "Cantrip",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Enchantment",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "10 ft.",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "1 hr./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "Cantrips are minor spells I studied by wizards during their apprenticeship, regardless of school.\n\nThe cantrip spell is a practice method for the apprentice, teaching him how to tap minute amounts of magical energy.\n\nOnce cast, the cantrip spell enables the caster to create minor magical effects for the duration of the spell.\n\nSo minor are these effects that they have severe limitations.\n\nThey are completely unable to cause a loss of hit points, cannot affect the concentration of spellcasters, and can only create small, obviously magical materials.\n\nFurthermore, materials created by a cantrip are extremely fragile and cannot be used as tools of any sort.\n\nLastly, a cantrip lacks the power to duplicate any other spell effects.\n\nWhatever manifestation the cantrip takes, it remains in effect only as long as the wizard concentrates.\n\nWizards typically use cantrips to impress common folk, amuse children, and brighten dreary lives.\n\nCommon tricks with cantrips include tinklings of ethereal music, brightening faded flowers, glowing balls that float over the caster's hand, puffs of wind to flicker candles, spicing up aromas and flavors of bland food, and little whirlwinds to sweep dust under rugs.\n\nCombined with the unseen servant spell, these are the tools to make housekeeping and entertaining simpler for the wizard.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 171,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 374,
      "name": "Change Self",
