    {
      "id": 381,
      "name": "Detect Phase",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Divination",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "10 x 60 ft.",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "2 rds./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "Creatures or objects that are phased - that is, in the Ethereal plane - can be detected by using this spell.\n\nThe spell affects a path 60 feet long and 10 feet wide; any phased creatures or objects in this area are revealed as soft, blue-glowing outlines visible to anyone in the vicinity.\n\nCreatures or effects detected by this spell include: phase spiders, ghost in their ethereal state, characters or creatures employing oil of etherealness, psionic etherealness or phasing, and all other similar effects.\n\nDoorways or portals to extradimensional spaces are also detected, although anything hidden within remains unseen.\n\nDetect phase does not reveal the location of creatures or objects concealed by magical invisibility or illusion.\n\nNote that detecting a phased monster doesn't necessarily give the caster the ability to attack it, but creatures such as phase spiders lose any special surprise bonuses they may receive if they are detected by using this spell.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 140,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 382,
      "name": "Detect Secret Passages and Portals",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Divination",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "10 x 10 ft. area/level",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "1 turn",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** enables a wizard to detect secret doors, compartments, caches, and similar devices.\n\nOnly passages, doors, or openings that have been deliberately constructed so as to escape detection are detected by this spell- a trap door buried beneath crates in a cellar, an illusionary wall, or an amulet left in a cluttered room would not be detected.\n\nThe wizard affects an area of 10 feet square per level, so a 4th-level wizard could search four sections of wall, floor, or ceiling.\n\nAny doorways or openings detected by this spell glow softly for one full turn.\n\nIt's possible that a wizard might not find a secret compartment in the area of effect if the compartment is behind or under another object that covers it completely.\n\n**This spell** only detects the doorway or opening; the wizard may have to search for a mechanism or catch that opens the door.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 140,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 383,
      "name": "Detect Undead",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Divination",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a bit of earth from a grave",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "60 ft.+ 10 ft./level",
      "casting_time": "1 rd.",
      "duration": "3 turns",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** enables the caster to detect all undead creatures out to the limit of the spell.\n\nThe area of effect extends in a path 10 feet wide and 60 feet long (plus 10 feet longer per level of the wizard), in the direction the caster is facing.\n\nScanning a direction requires one round, and the caster must be motionless.\n\nWhile the spell indicates direction, it does not give specific location or distance.\n\nIt detects undead through walls and obstacles but is blocked by 1 foot of solid stone, 1 yard of wood or loose earth, or a thin coating of metal.\n\nThe spell does not indicate the type of undead detected, only that undead are present.\n\nThe material component for this spell is a bit of earth from a grave.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 173,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 384,
      "name": "Dictation",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Conjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": false,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "blank page, scroll, or paper",
      "range": "10-ft. radius",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "1 turn/level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** animates a quill to write upon a prepared parchment any words spoken by the wizard, or those within 10 feet of them.\n\nThe quill functions as normal, needing to be refilled at an ink pot, but the magic of the spell prevents ink from dripping or running.\n\nThe text is as smooth as the paper and writing instrument allow for.\n\nIt is useful for recording conversations, verbal agreements, interrogations, or even notes or observations if the wizard doesn't want to take the time to write them down himself.\n\nGenerally, a person reading aloud takes about one to five minutes to read a page, depending on how many words are on page.\n\nIf a conversation moves too quickly for the quill to keep up, it will default to the caster's speech only.\n\nIf the caster speaks too quickly for the quill to keep up, it may begin to skip over words and make the text difficult to parse.\n\nForeign languages are not translated, although foreign words are given the correct alphabetic spelling in the wizard's native tongue; for example, the phrase \"cest la vie\" would appear as it does here, with no English translation, but a phrase or name in Arabic or Chinese would not be transcribed in those alphabets.\n\nMagical spells and invocations are not recorded, so this spell can't be used to create a backup copy of a scroll even as it's read by the wizard, but a clever wizard may be able to record a magical item's command word if an enemy within ranges uses it while the spell is in effect.\n\nThe material components for this spell is the blank page, scroll, or paper that the dictation will appear on, as well as quill and ink.\n\nThis must be prepared with a special wash of vinegar, which brings the cost to 10 gold pieces per page so readied.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 140,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 385,
      "name": "Enlarge",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a pinch of powdered iron",
      "range": "5 yds./level",
      "aoe": "1 creature or object",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "5 rds./level",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** causes instant growth of a creature or object, increasing both size and weight.\n\nIt can be cast only upon a single creature (or a symbiotic or community entity) or upon a single object that does not exceed ten cubic feet in volume per caster level.\n\nThe object or creature must be seen to be affected.\n\nIt grows by up to 10% per level of experience of the wizard, increasing this amount in height, width, and weight.\n\nMagical properties are not increased by this spell - a huge sword +1 is still only +1, a staff-sized wand is still only capable of its normal functions, a giant-sized potion merely requires a greater fluid intake to make its magical effects operate, etc.\n\nWeight, mass and strength are affected, though.\n\nThus, a table blocking a door would be heavier and more effective, a hurled stein would have more mass (and cause more damage), chains would be more massive, doors thicker, a thin line turned to a sizeable, longer rope, and so on.\n\nA creature's hit points, Armor Class, and attack rolls do not change, but damage rolls increase proportionally with size.\n\nFor example, a fighter at 160% normal size hits with his long sword and rolls a 6 for damage.\n\nThe adjusted damage roll is 10 (that is 6 x 1.6 = 9.6, rounded up).\n\nBonuses due to Strength, class, and magic are not altered.\n\nThe reverse spell, reduce, negates the enlarge spell or makes creatures or objects smaller.\n\nThe creature or object loses 10% of its original size for every level of the caster, to a minimum of 10% of the original size.\n\nThereafter, the size shrinks by one-foot increments to less than one foot, by one-inch increments to one inch, and by 1/10-inch increments to a minimum of 1/10 of an inch - the recipient cannot dwindle away to nothingness.\n\nFor example, a 16-foot-tall giant reduced by a 15th-level wizard (15 steps) would be reduced to 1.6 feet (in nine steps), then to 6/10 of a foot or 7.2 inches (in one step), and finally to 2.2 inches (in the last five steps).\n\nA shrinking object may damage weaker materials affixed to it, but an object will shrink only as long as the object itself is not damaged.\n\nUnwilling creatures are allowed a saving throw vs.\n\nspell.\n\nA rowboat that has a length of 14', a depth of 2', and a beam of 4' has a volume of 112 cubic feet.\n\nA rough volume measurement for a humanoid is: height cubed, divided by 24 (h³/24).\n\nThe material component of this spell is a pinch of powdered iron.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 173,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 386,
