      "material": true,
      "materials": "a drop of the liquid",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "1'-cube/level",
      "casting_time": "1 round",
      "duration": "Permanent",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** transmutes one type of liquid into an equal amount of a different, nonmagical fluid (water, wine, blood, oil, apple cider, etc.).\n\nThe caster must touch the fluid itself (not simply its container) for the spell to take effect.\n\nMagical liquids (such as potions) receive a saving throw vs.\n\ndisintegration with a +3 bonus to avoid the spell's effect.\n\nFluids can be transmuted only into nonmagical liquids; it is not possible to change a magical liquid into another type of magical liquid.\n\nPoisons may be rendered harmless through use of this spell, but the spell has no effect on poisons already consumed.\n\nLiving creatures are unaffected by the spell, excluding those from the elemental plane of water.\n\nSuch creatures are allowed a saving throw vs.\n\nspell.\n\nFailure results in ld4 points of damage per level of the caster, while success indicates half damage.\n\nOnly one creature can be affected by a single casting of this spell, regardless of the creature's size.\n\nThe material component is a drop of the liquid that the caster intends to create, which must be placed on the wizards tongue and consumed.\n\nCreating poisons through use of this spell is especially dangerous.",
      "source": "Tome of Magic",
      "page": 19,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 406,
      "name": "Mount",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Conjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a bit of hair from the type of animal to be conjured",
      "range": "10 yds.",
      "aoe": "1 mount",
      "casting_time": "1 turn",
      "duration": "2 hrs.+ 1 hr./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**By means of this spell**, the caster conjures a normal animal to serve him as a mount.\n\nThe animal serves willingly and well, but at the expiration of the spell duration it disappears, returning to its own place.\n\nThe type of mount gained by this spell depends on the level of the caster; of course, a caster can choose a lesser mount if desired.\n\nAvailable mounts include the following: Between 1st to 3rd level a mule or light horse Between 4th to 7th level a draft horse or war horse Between 8th to 12th level a camel Between 13th to 14th level an elephant (and howdah at 18th level) Starting at 15th level a griffon (and saddle at 18th level) The mount does not come with any riding gear, unless it is of a class lower than the caster would normally be entitled to; thus a 4th-level wizard can gain a war horse without saddle and harness, or a light horse with saddle and harness.\n\nThe statistics of the animal gained are typical of all creatures of the same class.\n\nThe mount disappears when slain.\n\nThe material component of the spell is a bit of hair from the type of animal to be conjured.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 177,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 407,
      "name": "Murdock's Feathery Flyer",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "an eagle's feather",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "The caster",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "1 turn/level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "Upon casting this spell, a feathery membrane grows under the wizards arms, extending along his sides all the way to his feet.\n\nThe membrane appears to merge with the caster's skin and clothing.\n\nIf the caster spreads his arms and jumps from a height, he may glide through the air.\n\nFor each foot of elevation, the wizard can glide five feet horizontally.\n\nThus, a wizard jumping from a 10-foot wall could glide up to 50 feet.\n\nGliding characters have a movement rate of 12 and Maneuverability Class E.\n\nA wizard attempting to carry more than his normal weight allowance plummets to the earth upon takeoff.\n\nWhen the spell expires, the feathers instantly disappear.\n\nIf the wizard is airborne, he immediately plummets toward the ground.\n\nThe material component is an eagle's feather.",
      "source": "Tome of Magic",
      "page": 19,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 408,
      "name": "Nahal's Reckless Dweomer",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Evocation",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "Special",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "5",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** is the wild mage's ultimate last-resort spell.\n\nWhen cast, the mage releases a sudden flood of wild magical energy in the hope of seizing and shaping that energy into a desired spell effect.\n\nThe attempt usually fails, but something almost always occurs in the process.\n\nBefore casting the spell, the mage announces the spell effect he is trying to create.\n\nThe mage must be able to cast the spell (i.e., have it in his spell books), but need not have it memorized.\n\nAfter announcing the spell (along with the target and any other conditions required by the spell), the wild mage casts Nahal's reckless dweomer.\n\nA burst of magical energy is released, which the wild mage tries to manipulate into the desired form.\n\nThe actual effect of the spell is rolled randomly on Table 2: Wild Surge Results.\n\nBecause the release of energy is planned by the mage, his level is added to the dice roll.\n\nIf the result indicates success, the mage has shaped the magical energy into the desired effect.\n\nMore often than not, the effect is completely unexpected.\n\nThe result may be beneficial to the mage or it may be completely disastrous; this is the risk the mage takes in casting Nahal's reckless dweomer.",
      "source": "Tome of Magic",
      "page": 20,
      "reversible": true
    },
    {
      "id": 409,
      "name": "Nystul's Magical Aura",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a small square of silk",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "1 rd.",
      "duration": "1 day/level",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**By means of this spell**, any one item of no more than five pounds weight per level of the spellcaster can be given an aura that is noticed by someone using magic detection.\n\nFurthermore, the caster can specify the type of magical aura that is detected (alteration, conjuration, etc.) and this effectively masks the item's actual aura, if any, unless the item's own aura is exceptionally powerful (if it is an artifact, for instance).\n\nIf the object bearing Nystul's magical aura has an identify spell cast on it or is similarly examined, the examiner has a 50% chance of recognizing that the aura has been placed to mislead the unwary.\n\nOtherwise, the aura is believed and no amount of testing reveals what the true magic is.\n\nThe component for this spell is a small square of silk, which must be passed over the object that receives the aura.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 177,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 410,
      "name": "Patternweave",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Divination",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a small hand lens",
      "range": "10 yards",
      "aoe": "10-foot square",
      "casting_time": "3",
      "duration": "1 round",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "Patternweave allows the caster to make sense of apparent chaos.\n\nThe caster can see such things as pottery shards reformed into a whole pot, shreds of paper formed into a page, scattered parts as a working machine, or specific trails appearing out of overlapping footprints.\n\nAfter casting the spell, the mage studies seemingly random elements-broken bits of glass, shreds of paper, intermingled trails, etc.\n\nThe items to be studied must be tangible-coded flashing lights, garbled speech, or thoughts of any kind cannot be studied.\n\nThe wizard must study the random elements for one round, after which the DM secretly makes a saving throw vs.\n\nspell for the wizard.\n\nIf the saving throw is failed, the spell fails.\n\nHowever, if the saving throw is successful, the caster sees in his mind the pattern these objects form.\n\nIf the items studied are truly random, no information is gained.\n\nAfter the caster has visualized the pattern, he can attempt to reassemble the parts into their original form.\n\nThis requires another saving throw vs.\n\nspell to determine whether the mage remembers sufficient details to accomplish the task.\n\nThe amount of time required and the quality of restoration vary according to the complexity of the pattern.\n\nReassembling a shredded map may be easy; reassembling a broken clock is significantly more difficult; rebuilding a shattered mosaic is extremely difficult.\n\nIn any case, the wizard can make only a reasonable copy of the item.\n\nHe can use this spell to restore works of art, but they will be worth only a small percentage of their original value.\n\nThe material component is a small hand lens through which the caster studies the objects.\n\nThe lens is not consumed in the casting.",
      "source": "Tome of Magic",
      "page": 20,
      "reversible": true
    },
    {
      "id": 411,
      "name": "Phantasmal Force",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a bit of fleece",
      "range": "60 yds.+ 10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "400 sq. ft.+ 100 sq. ft./level",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** creates the illusion of any object, creature, or force, as long as it is within the boundaries of the spell's area of effect.\n\nThe illusion is visual and affects all believing creatures (undead are immune) that view it.\n\nIt does not create sound, smell, or temperature.\n\nEffects that depend on these senses usually fail.\n\nThe illusion lasts until struck by an opponent - unless the spellcaster causes the illusion to react appropriately - or until the wizard ceases concentration upon the spell (due to desire, moving, or a successful attack that causes damage).\n\nSaving throws for illusions are explained under \"Illusions\" in Chapter 7: Magic and under \"Adjudicating Illusions\" at the beginning of Appendix 2.\n\nCreatures that disbelieve the illusion see it for what it is and add +4 to associates' saving throws if this knowledge can be communicated effectively.\n\nCreatures believing the illusion are subject to its effects, again as explained under Illusions.\n\nThe illusionary effect can be moved by the caster within the limits of the area of effect.\n\nThe DM has to rule on the effectiveness of this spell; detailed guidelines are outlined under \"Illusions\" in Chapter 7: Magic and under \"Adjudicating Illusions\" at the beginning of Appendix 2.\n\nThe material component of the spell is a bit of fleece.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 177,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 412,
      "name": "Protection From Evil",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Abjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "Creature touched",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "2 rds./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When this spell is cast, it creates a magical barrier around the recipient at a distance of 1 foot.\n\nThe barrier moves with the recipient and has three major effect: First, all attacks made by evil creatures against the protected creature suffer -2 penalties to attack rolls; any saving throws caused by such attacks are made with +2bonuses.\n\nSecond, any attempt to possess or exercise mental control over the protected creature is blocked by this spell.\n\nNote that the protection does not prevent a vampire's charm itself, but it does prevent the exercise of mental control through the barrier.\n\nLikewise, a possessing life force is merely kept out.\n\nIt would not be expelled if in place before the protection is cast.\n\nThird, the spell prevents bodily contact by creatures of an extraplanar or conjured nature.\n\nThis cause the natural weapon attacks require touching the protected being.\n\nAnimals or monsters summoned or conjured by spells or similar magic are likewise hedged from the character.\n\nThis protection ends if the protected character makes a melee attack against or tries to force the barrier against the blocked creature.\n\nTo complete this spell, the wizard must trace a 3-foot diameter circle on the floor with powdered silver.\n\n**This spell** can be reversed to become protection from good; the second and third benefits remain unchanged.\n\nThe material component for the reverse is a circle of powdered iron.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 177,
      "reversible": true
    },
    {
      "id": 413,
      "name": "Protection from Vermin",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Abjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": false,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a cone of pungent incense",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "Creature touched",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "2 rds./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** creates a magical barrier around the recipient, preventing the attacks of nonintelligent monsters of less than 1 Hit Die.\n\nCreatures in this category include normal centipedes, spiders, bats, and rats, but any monster with an Intelligence of low or better can ignore the spell's effects.\n\nThe barrier extend about one foot from the protected character's body and moves with him; vermin cannot tolerate the aura's touch and recoil from the character.\n\nAny attacks that require physical contact(bites, stings, claws, etc.) Automatically fail, but a creature with a ranged attack can still attack the spell's recipient.\n\nThe spell ends if the recipient attacks a creature he has been protected against, or tries to pin or trap the vermin by forcing the repelling barrier against them.\n\nThe material component for this spell is a cone of pungent incense burned in a tiny bronze censer containing osquip ashes.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 141,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 414,
      "name": "Ray of Fatigue",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Necromancy",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "10 yds. + 5 yds./level",
      "aoe": "1 creature",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "This nefarious spell affects the victim's life energies, increasing any fatigue or exhaustion currently possesses.\n\nAlter and well-rested characters suddenly become tired and sluggish, and characters who are already fatigue may be reduced to near-helplessness.\n\nIn effect, the ray adds one level of fatigue or encumbrance to the victim.\n\nModerately encumbered characters suffer a -1 penalty to attack rolls; heavily encumbered characters suffer a -2 penalty to attack rolls and a +1 Armor class penalty to attack rolls and a +3 Armor class penalty.(Assume that monsters suffer a -1 penalty to their attack rolls and reduce their movement rates by 33%).\n\nThe victim is allowed a saving throw to negate the spell's effects.\n\nIf you are using the fatigue rules from the Player's option; Combat &tactics book, this spell operates in a slightly different manner-fresh characters become fatigued, gaining one level of encumbrance; fatigued characters become exhausted, gaining two levels of encumbrance; and exhausted characters collapse in a quivering heap, unable to move or attack.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 142,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 415,
      "name": "Read Magic",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Divination",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a clear crystal or mineral prism",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "1 rd.",
      "duration": "2 rds./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "By means of a read magic spell, the wizard is able to read magical inscriptions on objects - books, scrolls, weapons, and the like - that would otherwise be totally unintelligible.\n\n(The personal books of the wizard, and works already magically read, are intelligible.) This deciphering does not normally invoke the magic contained in the writing, although it may do so in the case of a cursed scroll.\n\nFurthermore, once the spell is cast and the wizard has read the magical inscription, he is thereafter able to read that particular writing without recourse to the use of the read magic spell.\n\nThe duration of the spell is two rounds per level of experience of the spellcaster; the wizard can read one page or its equivalent per round.\n\nThe wizard must have a clear crystal or mineral prism, which is not expended, to cast the spell.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 178,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 416,
      "name": "Shield",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Evocation",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "5 rds./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When this spell is cast, an invisible barrier comes into being in front of the wizard.\n\nThis shield totally negates magic missile attacks.\n\nIt provides the equivalent protection of AC 2 against hand-hurled missiles (axes, darts, javelins, spears, etc.), AC 3 against small device-propelled missiles (arrows, bolts, bullets, manticore spikes, sling stones, etc.), and AC 4 against all other forms of attack.\n\nThe shield also adds a +1 bonus to the wizards saving throws against attacks that are basically frontal.\n\nNote that these benefits apply only if the attacks originate from in front of the wizard, where the shield can move to interpose itself.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 178,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 417,
      "name": "Shocking Grasp",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "Creature touched",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "1d8 +1/level",
      "description": "When the wizard casts this spell, he develops a powerful electrical charge that gives a jolt to the creature touched.\n\nThe spell remains in effect for one round per level of the caster or until it is discharged by the caster touching another creature.\n\nThe shocking grasp delivers 1d8 points of damage, plus 1 point per level of the wizard (e.g., a 2nd-level wizard would discharge a shock causing 1d8+2 points of damage).\n\nWhile the wizard must come close enough to his opponent to lay a hand on the opponent's body or upon an electrical conductor that touches the opponent's body, a like touch from the opponent does not discharge the spell.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 178,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 418,
      "name": "Sleep",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Enchantment",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a pinch of fine sand, rose petals, or a live cricket",
      "range": "30 yds.",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "5 rds./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When a wizard casts a sleep spell, he causes a comatose slumber to come upon one or more creatures (other than undead and certain other creatures specifically excluded from the spell's effects).\n\nAll creatures to be affected by the sleep spell must be within 30 feet of each other.\n\nThe number of creatures that can be affected is a function of Hit Dice or levels.\n\nThe spell affects 2d4 Hit Dice of monsters.\n\nMonsters with 4+3 Hit Dice (4 Hit Dice plus 3 hit points) or more are unaffected.\n\nThe center of the area of effect is determined by the spellcaster.\n\nThe creatures with the least Hit Dice are affected first, and partial effects are ignored.\n\nFor example, a wizard casts sleep at three kobolds, two gnolls, and an ogre.\n\nThe roll (2d4) result is 4.\n\nAll the kobolds and one gnoll are affected (1/2 + 1/2 + 1/2 + 2 = 3 1/2 Hit Dice).\n\nNote that the remainder is not enough to affect the last gnoll or the ogre.\n\nSlapping or wounding awakens affected creatures but normal noise does not.\n\nAwakening requires one entire round.\n\nMagically sleeping opponents can be attacked with substantial bonuses (see Combat, page 90).\n\nThe material component for this spell is a pinch of fine sand, rose petals, or a live cricket.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 178,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 419,
      "name": "Spider Climb",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a drop of bitumen and a live spider",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "Creature touched",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "3 rds.+ 1 rd./level",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "A spider climb spell enables the recipient to climb and travel upon vertical surfaces as well as a giant spider, or even hang upside down from ceilings.\n\nUnwilling victims must be touched and are then allowed a saving throw vs.\n\nspell to negate the effect.\n\nThe affected creature must have bare hands and feet in order to climb in this manner, at a movement rate of 6 (3 if at all encumbered).\n\nDuring the course of the spell, the recipient cannot handle objects that weigh less than a dagger (one pound), for such objects stick to his hands and feet.\n\nThus a wizard will find it virtually impossible to cast spells if under a spider climb spell.\n\nSufficient force can pull the recipient free; the DM can assign a saving throw based on circumstances, the strength of the force, and so on.\n\nFor example, a creature with a Strength of 12 might pull the subject free if the subject fails a saving throw vs.\n\nparalyzation (a moderately difficult saving throw).\n\nThe caster can end the spell effect with a word.\n\nThe material components of this spell are a drop of bitumen and a live spider, both of which must be eaten by the spell recipient.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 179,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 420,
      "name": "Spook",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "1 creature within 30 feet",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "A spook spell enables the wizard to play upon natural fears to cause the target creature to perceive the spellcaster as someone or something inimical.\n\nWithout actually knowing what this is, the wizard merely advances threateningly upon the creature.\n\nIf a successful saving throw vs.\n\nspell is not made, the creature turns and flees at maximum speed as far from the wizard as possible, though items carried are not dropped.\n\nThe creature has a saving throw penalty of -1 for every two experience levels of the caster, to a maximum of -6 at 12th level.\n\nNote that a natural (unmodified) roll of 20 automatically succeeds, regardless of saving throw penalties.\n\nAlthough the caster does not actually pursue the fleeing creature, a phantasm from its own mind does.\n\nEach round after the initial casting, the creature receives another saving throw, without penalty, until it successfully saves and the spell is broken.\n\nIn any event, the spell functions only against creatures with Intelligences of 2 or more, and undead are not affected at all.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 179,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 421,
      "name": "Taunt",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Enchantment",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a slug, which is hurled at the creatures",
      "range": "60 yds.",
      "aoe": "30-ft. radius",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "1 rd.",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "A taunt spell enables the caster to jape and jeer effectively at a single type of creature with an Intelligence of 2 or greater.\n\nThe caster need not speak the language of the creatures.\n\nHis words and sounds have real meaning for the subject creature or creatures: challenging, insulting, and generally irritating and angering the listeners.\n\nThose failing to save vs.\n\nspell rush forth in fury to do battle with the spellcaster.\n\nAll affected creatures attack the spellcaster in melee if physically capable of doing so, seeking to use body or hand-held weapons rather than missile weapons or spells.\n\nSeparation of the caster from the victim by an impenetrable or uncrossable boundary (a wall of fire, a deep chasm, a formation of set pikemen) causes the spell to break.\n\nIf the caster taunts a mixed group, he must choose the type of creature to be affected.\n\nCreatures commanded by a strong leader (i.e., with a Charisma bonus, with higher Hit Dice, etc.) might gain a saving throw bonus of +1 to +4, at the DMs discretion.\n\nIf used in conjunction with a ventriloquism spell, the creatures may attack the apparent source, depending upon their Intelligence, a leader's presence, and so on.\n\nThe material component is a slug, which is hurled at the creatures to be taunted.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 179,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 422,
      "name": "Tenser's Floating Disc",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Evocation",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a drop of mercury",
      "range": "20 yds.",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "3 turns+ 1 turn/level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "With this spell, the caster creates the slightly concave, circular plane of force known as Tenser's floating disc (after the famed wizard whose greed and ability to locate treasure are well known).\n\nThe disc is three feet in diameter and holds 100 pounds of weight per level of the wizard casting the spell.\n\nThe disc floats at approximately three feet above the ground at all times and remains level.\n\nIt floats along horizontally within its range of 20 yards at the command of the caster, and will accompany him at a movement rate of no more than 6.\n\nIf unguided, it maintains a constant interval of six feet between itself and the wizard.\n\nIf the spellcaster moves beyond range (by moving faster, or by such means as a teleport spell, or by trying to take it more than three feet from the surface beneath it), or if the spell duration expires, the floating disc winks out of existence and whatever it was supporting crashes to the surface beneath it.\n\nThe material component of the spell is a drop of mercury.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 179,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
