      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "The unseen servant is a non-visible, mindless, and shapeless force, used to step and fetch, open unstuck doors, and hold chairs, as well as to clean and mend.\n\nIt is not strong, but unfailingly obeys the command of the wizard.\n\nIt can carry out only one activity at a time and can move only light-weight items - carry a maximum of 20 pounds or push or pull 40 pounds across a smooth surface.\n\nIt can open only normal doors, drawers, lids, etc.\n\nThe unseen servant cannot fight, nor can it be killed, as it is a force rather than a creature.\n\nIt can be magically dispelled, or eliminated after receiving 6 points of damage from area-effect spells, breath weapons, or similar attacks.\n\nIf the caster attempts to send it beyond the allowed radius, the spell ends immediately.\n\nThe material components of the spell are a piece of string and a bit of wood.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 180,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 424,
      "name": "Ventriloquism",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": false,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a parchment rolled up into a small cone",
      "range": "10 yds./level, max 90 yds.",
      "aoe": "1 creature or object",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "4 rds.+ 1 rd./level",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** enables the wizard to make his voice, or the subject of the spell's voice, seem to issue from someplace else, such as from another creature, a statue, from behind a door, down a passage, etc.\n\nThe spellcaster can speak in any language that he knows, or make any sound that he can normally make.\n\nWith respect to such voices and sounds, anyone rolling a successful saving throw vs.\n\nspell with a -2 penalty detects the ruse.\n\nIf cast in conjunction with other illusions, the DM may rule greater penalties or disallow an independent saving throw against this spell in consideration of its contribution to the total effect of the combined illusion.\n\nThe material component of this spell is a parchment rolled up into a small cone.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 180,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 425,
      "name": "Wall of Fog",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Evocation",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a pinch of split dried peas",
      "range": "30 yds.",
      "aoe": "20-ft. cube+ 10-ft. cube/level",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "2d4 rds.+ 1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "By casting this spell, the wizard creates a billowing wall of misty vapors in any area within the spell range.\n\nThe wall of fog obscures all sight, normal and infravision, beyond two feet.\n\nThe caster may create less vapor if he wishes.\n\nThe wall must be a roughly cubic or rectangular mass, at least ten feet wide in its smallest dimension.\n\nThe misty vapors persist for three or more rounds.\n\nTheir duration can be halved by a moderate wind, and they can be blown away by a strong wind.\n\nThe material component is a pinch of split dried peas.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 180,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 426,
      "name": "Wizard Mark",
      "level": "1",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a pinch of diamond dust (about 10 gp worth) and a pigment or pigments",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "Up to 1 sq. ft.",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "Permanent",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When this spell is cast, the wizard is able to inscribe, visibly or invisibly, his personal rune or mark, as well as up to six additional characters of smaller size.\n\nA wizard mark spell enables the caster to etch the rune upon stone, metal, or any softer substance without harm to the material upon which the mark is placed.\n\nIf an invisible mark is made, a detect magic spell will cause it to glow and be visible (though not necessarily understandable).\n\nDetect invisibility, true seeing, a gem of seeing, or a robe of eyes will likewise expose an invisible wizard mark.\n\nA read magic spell will reveal the maker's words, if any.\n\nThe mark cannot be dispelled, but it can be removed by the caster or by an erase spell.\n\nIf cast on a living being, normal wear gradually causes the mark to fade.\n\nThe material components for this spell are a pinch of diamond dust (about 100 gp worth) and a pigment or pigments for the coloration of the mark.\n\nIf the mark is to be invisible, the pigments are still used, but the caster uses a stylus of some sort rather than his finger.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 180,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 427,
      "name": "Alter Self",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "The caster",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "3d4 rds.+ 2 rds./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When this spell is cast, the wizard can alter his appearance and form - including clothing and equipment - to appear taller or shorter; thin, fat, or in between; human, humanoid, or any other generally man-shaped bipedal creature.\n\nThe caster may only turn into other races or species they are personally familiar with.\n\nSimply reading about an Aarakocra is not enough to take the form of one.\n\nThe caster's body can undergo a limited physical alteration and his size can be changed up to 50%.\n\nIf the form selected has wings, the wizard can actually fly, but at only one-third the speed of a true creature of that type, and with a loss of two maneuverability classes (to a minimum of E).\n\nIf the form has gills, the caster can breathe under water as long as the spell lasts.\n\nHowever, the caster does not gain any multiple attack routines or additional damage allowed to an assumed form.\n\nThe caster's attack rolls, Armor Class, and saving throws do not change.\n\nThe spell does not confer special abilities, attack forms, or defenses.\n\nOnce the new form is chosen, it remains for the duration of the spell.\n\nThe caster can change back into his own form at will; this ends the spell immediately.\n\nA caster who is slain automatically returns to his normal form.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 180,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 428,
      "name": "Bind",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Enchantment",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a rope",
      "range": "30 yds.",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When this spell is employed, the wizard can command any non-living ropelike object, including string, yarn, cord, line, rope, or even a cable.\n\nThe spell affects 50 feet of normal rope (one-inch diameter), plus five feet per caster level.\n\nThis length is reduced by 50% for every additional inch of thickness and increases by 50% for each 1/2 inch less.\n\nThe possible commands are Coil (form a neat, coiled stack), Coil & Knot, Loop, Loop & Knot, Tie & Knot, and the reverses of all of the above (Uncoil, etc.).\n\nOne command can be given each round.\n\nThe rope can only enwrap a creature or an object within one foot of it - it does not snake outward - so it must be thrown or hurled near the intended target.\n\nNote that the rope itself, and any knots tied in it, are not magical.\n\nA typical rope might be AC 6 and take 4 points of slashing damage before breaking.\n\nThe rope does not inflict damage of any type, but it can be used as a trip line or to entangle a single opponent who fails a saving throw vs.\n\nspell.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 181,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 429,
      "name": "Blindness",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": false,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "30 yds.+ 10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "1 creature",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "The blindness spell causes the victim to become blind, able to see only a grayness before its eyes.\n\nVarious cure spells will not remove this effect, and only a dispel magic or the spellcaster can do away with the blindness if the creature fails its initial saving throw vs.\n\nspell.\n\nA blinded creature suffers a -4 penalty to its attack rolls, and its opponents gain a +4 bonus to their attack rolls.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 181,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 430,
      "name": "Blur",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "The caster",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "3 rds.+ 1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**When a blur spell is cast**, the wizard causes the outline of his form to become blurred, shifting and wavering.\n\nThis distortion causes all missile and melee combat attacks against the caster to be made with -4 penalties on the first attempt and -2 penalties on all successive attacks.\n\nIt also grants the wizard a +1 bonus to his saving throw for any direct magical attack.\n\nA detect invisibility spell will not counter this effect, but the 5th-level clerical spell true seeing and similar magic will.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 181,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 431,
      "name": "Cat's Grace",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Abjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a few whiskers from an elven cat.",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "Creature touched",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "1 hr./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "Just as a strength spell can increase a subject's physical power for a time, cat's grace can enhance a subject's Dexterity.\n\nAll abilities and skills that are Dexterity-based may be affected by an enhanced Dexterity score, including a subject's reaction adjustment, missile attack adjustment, defensive adjustment, Dexterity-based proficiency scores, and adjustments to their abilities.\n\nThe exact amount of Dexterity gained depends on the subject's class; multi-classed character's use the favorable die.\n\nRouges: d8; Wizards: d6; Warriors: d6; Priests: d4.\n\nThe spell cannot confer a dexterity score of 20 or more and is not cumulative with other dexterity enhancing magical or psionic powers.\n\nSubjects without dexterity scores gain a bonus of 1 to AC and a +1 to attack rolls with missiles for the duration of the spell.\n\nThe material component for this spell is a few whiskers from an elven cat.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 142,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 432,
      "name": "Chaos Shield",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Abjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "The caster",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "1d10  rounds +2 rounds/level",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "Following the discovery of wild magic came the discovery of wild surges and the personal danger such surges create.\n\nAfter several wild mages destroyed themselves by rather spectacular means (or suffered very odd side effects), the chaos shield was created as protection from these surges.\n\n**This spell** imbues the wild mage with special protection against the effects of wild surges.\n\nIt protects only against wild surges caused by the caster's own spells, not from the effects of another mage's surges.\n\nWhen a wild surges affects a caster protected by chaos shield, he is allowed a saving throw vs.\n\nmagic.\n\nIf the saving throw is successful, the effect of the surge on the caster is negated.\n\nIf the saving throw is failed, the caster is affected normally by the surge.\n\nThe spell does not protect against wild surges that might be caused by its own casting.\n\nThe chaos shield protects of a wild surge for other characters who might be in the area of effect.\n\nThe caster cannot voluntarily cancel the protection once he has learned the nature of a wild surge; the chaos shield protects from both good and harmful effects.\n\nThus, if a wild surge resulted in a heal spell for all characters within 10 feet of the caster, the protected caster might not benefit, while all others in the radius would be healed.\n\nThe spell remains in effect until it negates a wild surge or the spell duration expires.",
      "source": "Tome of Magic",
      "page": 21,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 433,
      "name": "Continual Light",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "60 yds.",
      "aoe": "60-ft. radius",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "Permanent",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** is similar to a light spell, except that it is as bright as full daylight and lasts until negated by magical darkness or by a dispel magic spell.\n\nCreatures who suffer penalties in bright light suffer them in this spell's area of effect.\n\nAs with the light spell, it can be cast into the air, onto an object, or at a creature.\n\nIn the third case, the spell affects the space about one foot behind a creature that successfully rolls its saving throw vs.\n\nspell.\n\nNote that this spell can also blind a creature if it is successfully cast upon the creature's attack rolls, saving throws, and Armor Class by 4.\n\nIf the spell is cast on a small object that is then placed in a light-proof covering, the spell's effects are blocked until the covering is removed.\n\nA continual light brought into an area of magical darkness (or vice versa) is temporarily negated so that the otherwise prevailing light conditions exist in the overlapping areas of effect.\n\nA direct casting of continual light against a similar or weaker magical darkness cancels both.\n\n**This spell** eventually consumes the material it is cast upon, but the process takes far longer than the time in the typical campaign.\n\nExtremely hard and expensive materials can last hundreds or even thousands of years.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 181,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 434,
      "name": "Darkness, 15' Radius",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a bit of bat fur and either a drop of pitch or a piece of coal",
      "range": "10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "15-ft. radius",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "1 turn+ 1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** causes total, impenetrable darkness in the area of effect.\n\nInfravision is useless.\n\nNeither normal nor magical light works unless a light or continual light spell is used.\n\nIn the former event, the darkness spell is negated by the light spell and vice versa.\n\nThe material components of this spell are a bit of bat fur and either a drop of pitch or a piece of coal.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 181,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 435,
      "name": "Deafness",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "beeswax",
      "range": "60 yds.",
      "aoe": "1 creature",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "The deafness spell causes the recipient to become totally deaf and unable to hear any sounds.\n\nThe victim is allowed a saving throw vs.\n\nspell.\n\nAn affected creature has a -1 penalty to its surprise rolls unless its other senses are unusually keen.\n\nDeafened spellcasters have a 20% chance to miscast any spell with a verbal component.\n\nThis deafness can be done away with only by means of a dispel magic spell or by the spellcaster.\n\nThe material component of this spell is beeswax.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 181,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 436,
      "name": "Deeppockets",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Enchantment",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "tiny golden needle and a strip of fine cloth",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "1 garment",
      "casting_time": "1 turn",
      "duration": "12 hrs.+ 1 hr./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** enables the wizard to specially prepare a garment so as to hold far more than it normally could.\n\nA finely sewn gown or robe of high quality material (at least 50gp value) is fashioned so as to contain numerous hand-sized pockets.\n\nOne dozen is the minimum number.\n\nThe deeppockets spell then enables these pockets to hold a total of 100 pounds (five cubic feet in volume) as if it were only 10 pounds of weight.\n\nFurthermore, there are no discernible bulges where the special pockets are.\n\nAt the time of casting, the caster can instead chose to have 10 pockets each holding 10 pounds (1/2 cubic foot volume each).\n\nIf the robe or like garment is sewn with 100 or more pockets (200gp minimum cost), 100 pockets can be created to contain one pound of weight and 1/6 cubic foot volume each.\n\nEach special pocket is actually an extradimensional holding space.\n\nIf the spell duration expires while there is material within the enchanted pockets, or if a successful dispel magic is cast upon the enchanted garment, all the material suddenly appears around the wearer and immediately falls to the ground.\n\nThe caster can also cause all the pockets to empty with a single command.\n\nIn addition to the garment, which is reusable, the material components of this spell are a tiny golden needle and a strip of fine cloth given a half-twist and fastened at the ends.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 182,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 437,
      "name": "Detect Evil",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Divination",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "60 yds.",
      "aoe": "10-ft. path",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "5 rds./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "This spell discovers emanations of evil intent.\n\n- It detects the **evil** alignment or malicious purpose.\n- Not useful for detecting **cursed** items or traps unless they are directly tied to evil magic or beings.\n- Can be **blocked** by 1 foot of stone, 1 inch of metal, or 3 feet of wood or dirt.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 182,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 438,
      "name": "Detect Invisibility",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Divination",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a pinch of talc and a small sprinkling of powdered silver",
      "range": "10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "10-foot path",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "5 rds./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When the wizard casts a detect invisibility spell, he is able to see clearly any objects or beings that are invisible, as well as any that are astral, ethereal, or out of phase.\n\nIn addition, it enables the wizard to detect hidden or concealed creatures (e.g., thieves in shadows, halflings in underbrush, and so on).\n\nIt does not reveal the method of concealment or invisibility, except in the case of astral travelers (where the silver cord can be seen).\n\nIt does not reveal illusions or enable the caster to see through physical objects.\n\nDetection is in the wizards line of sight along a ten-foot-wide path to the range limit.\n\nThe material components of this spell are a pinch of talc and a small sprinkling of powdered silver.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 182,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 439,
      "name": "Displace Self",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": false,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a small strip of leather from a displacer beast",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "The caster",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "Emulating the natural ability of the displacer beast, this spell causes the caster to appear to be about two feet away from his true location.\n\nAny creature making a melee or missile attack against the caster automatically misses with his first attempt and suffers a -2 penalty on all subsequent attack rolls.\n\nIn addition, the wizard also gains a +2 bonus on saving throws for any spell or special attack aimed directly at him, not at any other characters or the area around him.\n\nThe only spell that will reveal the caster's true location is true seeing.\n\nThe material component for this spell is a small strip of leather made from displacer beast hide that is twisted into a loop.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 142,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 440,
      "name": "ESP",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Divination",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a copper piece",
      "range": "5 yds./level, 90 yds. max",
      "aoe": "1 creature per probe",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When an ESP spell is used, the caster is able to detect the surface thoughts of any creatures in range - except for those of undead and creatures without minds (as we know them).\n\nThe ESP is stopped by two or more feet of rock, two or more inches of any metal other than lead, or a thin sheet of lead foil.\n\nThe wizard employing the spell is able to probe the surface thoughts of one creature per round, getting simple instinctual thoughts from lower order creatures.\n\nProbes can continue on the same creature from round to round or can move on to other creatures.\n\nThe caster can use the spell to help determine if a creature lurks behind a door, for example, but the ESP does not always reveal what sort of creature it is.\n\nIf used as part of a program of interrogation, an intelligent and wary subject receives an initial saving throw.\n\nIf successful, the creature successfully resists and the spell reveals no additional information.\n\nIf the saving throw is failed, the caster may learn additional information, according to the DMs ruling.\n\nThe creature's Wisdom adjustment applies, as may additional bonuses up to +4, based on the sensitivity of the information sought.\n\nThe material component of this spell is a copper piece.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 182,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 441,
      "name": "Flaming Sphere",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Evocation",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a bit of tallow, a pinch of sulphur, and a dusting of powdered iron",
      "range": "10 yds.",
      "aoe": "3-ft. radius sphere",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "A flaming sphere spell creates a burning globe of fire within ten yards of the caster.\n\nThis sphere rolls in whichever direction the wizard points, at a rate of 30 feet per round.\n\nIt rolls over barriers less than four feet tall, such as furniture, low walls, etc.\n\nFlammable substances are set afire by contact with the sphere.\n\nCreatures in contact with the globe must successfully save vs.\n\nspell or suffer 2d4 points of fire damage.\n\nThose within five feet of the sphere's surface must also save or suffer 1d4 points of heat damage.\n\nA successful saving throw means no damage is suffered.\n\nThe DM may adjust the saving throws if there is little or no room to dodge the sphere.\n\nThe sphere moves as long as the spellcaster actively directs it, otherwise it merely stays at rest and burns.\n\nIt can be extinguished by the same means as any normal fire of its size.\n\nThe surface of the sphere has a spongy, yielding consistency and so does not cause damage except by its flame.\n\nIt cannot push unwilling creatures aside or batter down large obstacles.\n\nThe material components are a bit of tallow, a pinch of sulphur, and a dusting of powdered iron.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 182,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 442,
      "name": "Fog cloud",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "10 yds.",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "4 rds.+ 1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "The fog cloud spell can be cast in one of two ways, at the caster's option: as a large, stationary bank of normal fog, or as a harmless fog that resembles the 5th-level wizard spell cloudkill.\n\nAs a fog bank, this spell creates a fog of any size and shape up to a maximum 20-foot cube per caster level.\n\nThe fog obscures all sight, normal and infravision, beyond two feet.\n\nAs a cloudkill-like fog, this is a billowing mass of ghastly, yellowish-green vapors, measuring 40 feet x 20 feet x 20 feet.\n\nThis moves away from the caster at 10 feet per round.\n\nThe vapors are heavier than air and sink to the lowest level, even pouring down sinkholes and den openings.\n\nVery thick vegetation breaks up the fog after it has moved 20 feet into the vegetation.\n\nThe only effect of either version is to obscure vision.\n\nA strong breeze will disperse either effect in one round, while a moderate breeze will reduce the spell duration by 50%.\n\nThe spell cannot be cast under water.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 183,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 443,
      "name": "Fools' Gold",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "Gold",
      "range": "10 yds.",
      "aoe": "10 cu. in./level",
      "casting_time": "1 rd.",
      "duration": "1 hr./level",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "Copper coins can temporarily be changed to gold pieces, or brass items turned to solid gold, for the spell duration by means of this magic.\n\nThe area of effect is ten cubic inches per level - i.e., a 1\" x 1\" x 10\" volume or equivalent, equal to about 150gold coins.\n\nAny creature viewing the \"gold\" is entitled to a saving throw vs.\n\nspell, which can be modified by the creature's Wisdom; for every level of the wizard, the creature must subtract 1 from his dice roll.\n\nThus it is unlikely that fools' gold will be detected if it was created by a high-level caster.\n\nIf the \"gold\" is struck hard by an object of cold-wrought iron, there is a slight chance it will revert to its natural state, depending on the material component used to create the - \"gold.\" If a 25-gp citrine is powdered and sprinkled over the metal as this spell is cast, the chance that cold iron will return it to its true nature is 30%; if a 50-gp amber stone is powdered and used, there is a 25% chance that iron will dispel the magic; if a 250-gp topaz is powdered, the chance drops to 10%; if a 500-gp oriental (corundum) topaz is powdered, there is only a 1% chance that the cold iron will reveal that it is fools' gold.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 183,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 444,
      "name": "Forget",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Enchantment",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "30 yds.",
      "aoe": "1-4 creatures in a 20-ft. cube",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "Permanent",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**By means of this spell**, the spellcaster causes creatures within the area of effect to forget the events of the previous round (the one minute of time previous to the utterance of the spell).For every three levels of experience of the spellcaster, another minute of past time is forgotten.\n\nThis does not negate charm, suggestion, geas, quest, or similar spells, but it is possible that the being who placed such magic upon the recipient could be forgotten.\n\nFrom one to four creatures can be affected, at the discretion of the caster.\n\nIf only one is to be affected, the recipient saves vs.\n\nspell with a -2 penalty; if two, they save with -1 penalties; if three or four are to be affected, they save normally.\n\nAll saving throws are adjusted by Wisdom.\n\nA priest's heal or restoration spell, if specially cast for this purpose, will restore the lost memories, as will a limited wish or wish, but no other means will do so.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 183,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
