      "duration": "1d4 rds.+ 1/level",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** creates a cloud of glittering golden particles within the area of effect.\n\nThose in the area must roll a successful saving throw vs.\n\nspell or be blinded (-4 penalties to attack rolls, saving throws, and Armor Class) for 1d4+1 rounds.\n\nIn addition, all within the area are covered by the dust, which cannot be removed and continues to sparkle until it fades.\n\nNote that this reveals invisible creatures.\n\nThe dust fades in 1d4 rounds plus one round per caster level.\n\nThus glitterdust cast by a 3rd-level wizard lasts for four to seven rounds.\n\nThe material component is ground mica.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 183,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 446,
      "name": "Hornung's Baneful Deflector",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Evocation",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a small prism",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "One creature",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "2 rounds/level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** partially surrounds the recipient in a shimmering, hemispherical field of force.\n\nThe field is transparent and moves with the subject, forming a shell about one foot away from his body.\n\nThe shell serves as a shield against all forms of individually targeted missile attacks (including magic missiles and other spells).\n\nThe caster designates the position of the shell (protecting the front, rear, side, or top of the recipient).\n\nThe spell does not protect against area effect spells or other attacks that strike several creatures at once.\n\nWhenever an individual missile attack is directed at a protected creature, the baneful deflector activates.\n\nInstead of striking the target creature, the missile's target is determined randomly among all creatures within a 15-foot hemisphere of the protected creature, including the protected creature.\n\nThe missile then changes course toward its new target with normal chances to hit.\n\nIf the new target is beyond the range of the missile, no target is hit.\n\nIf the protected creature is struck, the spell immediately fails.\n\nIf several people are protected by baneful deflector, a missile will change course several times before reaching its target.\n\nThe material component is a small prism that shatters when the spell is cast.",
      "source": "Tome of Magic",
      "page": 21,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 447,
      "name": "Hypnotic Pattern",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": false,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a glowing stick of incense or a crystal rod filled with phosphorescent material",
      "range": "30 yds.",
      "aoe": "30-ft. cube",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When this spell is cast, the wizard creates a weaving, twisting pattern of subtle colors in the air.\n\nThis pattern causes any creature looking at it to become fascinated and stand gazing at it as long as the spellcaster maintains the display, plus two rounds there after.\n\nThe spell can captivate a maximum of 24 levels, or Hit Dice, of creatures (e.g., 24 creatures with 1 Hit Die each, 12 with 2 Hit Dice, etc).\n\nAll creatures affected must be within the area of effect, and each is entitled to a saving throw vs.\n\nspell.\n\nA damage inflicting attack on an affected creature frees it from the spell immediately.\n\nThe mage need not utter a sound, but he must gesture appropriately while holding a glowing stick of incense or a crystal rod filled with phosphorescent material.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 183,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 448,
      "name": "Improved Phantasmal Force",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a bit of fleece",
      "range": "60 yds.+ 10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "200 sq. ft.+ 50 sq. ft./level",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "Like the 1st-level phantasmal force spell, this spell creates the illusion of any object, creature, or force, as long as it is within the spell's area of effect.\n\nThe spellcaster can maintain the illusion with minimal concentration, thus he can move at half normal speed (but not cast other spells).\n\nSome minor sounds are included in the effects of the spell, but not understandable speech.\n\nAlso, the improved phantasm continues for two rounds after the wizard ceases to concentrate upon it.\n\nThe material component is a bit of fleece.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 184,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 449,
      "name": "Insatiable Thirst",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Enchantment",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "5 yards/level",
      "aoe": "One creature",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "1 round/level",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** instills in the victim an uncontrollable desire to drink.\n\nThe victim is allowed a saving throw to avoid the effect.\n\nIf the roll is failed, the creature must consume any potable liquids it can find (including magical potions, which might result in strange effects if potions are mixed).\n\nAlthough poisons are not considered potable, a victim may not realize that a liquid is poisonous.\n\nThe victim will not consume a liquid he knows to be poisonous.\n\nNo matter how much the creature drinks, its magical thirst is not quenched until the spell ends.\n\nDuring this time, the creature can do nothing but drink or look for liquids to drink.\n\nVictims of this spell believe they are dying of thirst and (depending upon their nature) may be willing to kill for drinkable fluids.",
      "source": "Tome of Magic",
      "page": 21,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 450,
      "name": "Invisibility",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "an eyelash and a bit of gum arabic",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "Creature touched",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "1 day",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** causes the creature touched to vanish from sight and be undetectable by normal vision or even infravision.\n\nOf course, the invisible creature is not magically silenced, and certain other conditions can render the creature detectable.\n\nEven allies cannot see the invisible creature or his gear, unless these allies can normally see invisible things or employ magic to do so.\n\nItems dropped or put down by the invisible creature become visible, items picked up disappear if tucked into the clothing or pouches worn by the creature.\n\nNote, however, that light never becomes invisible, although a source of light can become so (thus, the effect is that of a light with no visible source).\n\nThe spell remains in effect until it is magically broken or dispelled, until the wizard or recipient cancels it, until the recipient casts a spell, attacks, or have any significant impacts.\n\nThus, the invisible being can open doors, talk, eat, climb stairs, etc., but as soon as he begins to cast a spell, he immediately becomes visible.\n\nMaking an attack breaks the invisibility on impact, enables him to attack first.\n\nSignificant impacts include taking damage from an external source (attacks, falls, and fire; not phantasms, toxins, and freezing) All highly Intelligent (Intelligence 13 or more) creatures with 10 or more Hit Dice or levels of experience have a chance to detect invisible objects (they roll saving throws vs.\n\nspell; success means they noticed the invisible object).\n\nThe material components of the invisibility spell are an eyelash and a bit of gum arabic, the former encased in the latter.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 184,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 451,
      "name": "Irritation",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a leaf from poison ivy, oak, or sumac",
      "range": "10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "1-4 creatures in a 15-ft. radius",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "An irritation spell affects the epidermis of the subject creatures.\n\nCreatures with very thick or insensitive skins (such as buffalo, elephants, scaled creatures, etc.) are basically unaffected.\n\nThere are two versions of the spell, either of which can be cast from the standard preparation: Itching.\n\nWhen cast, this causes each subject to feel an instant itching sensation on some portion of its body.\n\nIf one round is not immediately spent scratching the irritated area, the creature is so affected that the next three rounds are spent squirming and twisting, effectively worsening its Armor Class by 4 and its attack rolls by 2 during this time.\n\nSpell preparations are ruined in the first round this spell is in effect, but not in the following three rounds.\n\nDoing nothing but scratching the itch for a full round prevents the rest of the effect.\n\nIf cast at one creature, the saving throw has a -3 penalty; if cast at two creatures, the saving throw has a -1 penalty; and if cast at three or four creatures, the saving throw is normal.\n\nRash.\n\n**When a rash is cast, the subject notices nothing for 1d4 rounds, but thereafter its entire skin breaks out in red welts that itch.\n\nThe rash persists until either a cure disease or dispel magic spell is cast** upon it.\n\nIt lowers Charisma by 1 point per day for each of four days (i.e., maximum Charisma loss is 4 points).\n\nAfter one week, Dexterity is lowered by 1 point also.\n\nSymptoms vanish immediately upon the removal of the rash, and all statistics return to normal.\n\nThis can be cast at one creature only, with a saving throw penalty of -2.\n\nThe material component for this spell is a leaf from poison ivy, oak, or sumac.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 184,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 452,
      "name": "Knock",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": false,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "60 yds.",
      "aoe": "10 sq. ft./level",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "The knock spell opens stuck, barred, locked, held, or wizard-locked doors.\n\nIt opens secret doors, as well as locked or trick-opening boxes or chests.\n\nIt also loosens welds, shackles, or chains.\n\nIf used to open a wizard-locked door, the spell does not remove the former spell, but simply suspends its functioning for one turn.\n\nIn all other cases, it permanently opens locks or welds - although the former could be closed and locked again later.\n\nIt does not raise barred gates or similar impediments (such as a portcullis), nor does it affect ropes, vines, and the like.\n\nNote that the effect is limited by the area; a 3rd-level wizard can cast a knock spell on a door of 30 square feet or less (for example, a standard 4-ft.\n\nx 7-ft.\n\ndoor).\n\nEach spell can undo up to two means of preventing egress through a portal.\n\nThus if a door is locked, barred, and held, or triple locked, opening it requires two knock spells.\n\nIn all cases, the location of the door or item must be known - the spell cannot be used against a wall in hopes of discovering a secret door.\n\nThe reverse spell, lock, closes and locks a door or similar closure, provided there is a physical mechanism.\n\nIt does not create a weld, but it locks physically operated locking mechanisms, set bars, and so on, up to two functions.\n\nIt cannot affect a portcullis.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 184,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 453,
      "name": "Know Alignment",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Divination",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "10 yds.",
      "aoe": "1 creature or object per 2 rds.",
      "casting_time": "1 rd.",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "A know alignment spell enables the wizard to read the aura of a creature or an aligned object (unaligned objects reveal nothing).\n\nThe caster must remain stationary and concentrate on the subject for two full rounds.\n\nA creature is allowed a saving throw vs.\n\nspell and, if successful, the caster learns nothing about that particular creature from the casting.\n\nIf the caster concentrates on a creature or object for only one round, he can learn only its alignment with respect to law and chaos.\n\nCertain magical devices negate the know alignment spell.\n\nThe reverse, undetectable alignment, conceals the alignment of an object or creature for 24 hours - even from a know alignment spell.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 185,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 454,
      "name": "Leomund's Trap",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a piece of iron pyrite and a special dust requiring 200 gp to prepare",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "Object touched",
      "casting_time": "3 rds.",
      "duration": "Permanent",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "This false trap is designed to fool a thief or other character attempting to pilfer the spellcaster's goods.\n\nThe wizard places the spell upon any small mechanism or device, such as a lock, hinge, hasp, screw-on cap, ratchet, etc.\n\nAny character able to detect traps, or who uses any spell or device enabling trap detection, is 100% certain a real trap exists.\n\nOf course, the spell is illusory and nothing happens if the trap is sprung; its primary purpose is to frighten away thieves or make them waste precious time.\n\nThe material component of the spell is a piece of iron pyrite touched to the object to be trapped while the object is sprinkled with a special dust requiring 200 gp to prepare.\n\nIf another Leomund's trap is within 50 feet when the spell is cast, then the casting fails.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 185,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 455,
      "name": "Levitate",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "either a small leather loop or a piece of golden wire",
      "range": "20 yds./level",
      "aoe": "1 creature or object",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "1 turn/level",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**When a levitate spell is cast**, the wizard can place it upon his person, upon an object, or upon a single creature, subject to a maximum weight limit of 100 pounds per level of experience (e.g., a 3rd-level wizard can levitate up to 300 pounds maximum).\n\nIf the spell is cast upon the wizard, he can move vertically up or down at a movement rate of 2 per round.\n\nIf cast upon an object or another creature, the wizard can levitate it at the same speed according to his command.\n\nHorizontal movement is not empowered by this spell, but the recipient could push along the face of a cliff, for example, to move laterally.\n\nThe spellcaster can cancel the spell as desired.\n\nIf the subject of the spell is unwilling, or the object is in the possession of a creature, a saving throw vs.\n\nspell is allowed to determine if the levitate spell affects it.\n\nOnce cast, the spell requires no concentration, except when changing height.\n\nA levitating creature attempting to use a missile weapon finds himself increasingly unstable; the first attack has an attack roll penalty of -1, the second -2, and the third -3, etc., up to a maximum of -5.\n\nA full round spent stabilizing allows the creature to begin again at -1.\n\nLack of leverage makes it impossible to cock a medium or heavy crossbow.\n\nThe material component of this spell is either a small leather loop or a piece of golden wire bent into a cup shape with a long shank on one end.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 185,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 456,
      "name": "Locate Object",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Divination",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a forked twig",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "20 yards/level",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** aids in locating a known or familiar object.\n\nThe wizard casts the spell, slowly turns, and senses when he is facing in the direction of the object to be located, provided the object is within range, i.e., 60 yards for 3rd-level wizards, 80 yards for 4th, 100 yards for 5th, etc.\n\nThe spell can locate such objects as apparel, jewelry, furniture, tools, weapons, or even a ladder or stairway.\n\nNote that attempting to find a specific item, such as jewelry or a crown, requires an accurate mental image; if the image is not close enough to the actual, the spell does not work.\n\nDesired but unique objects cannot be located by this spell unless they are known by the caster.\n\nThe spell is blocked by lead, but not silver.\n\nCreatures cannot be found by this spell.\n\nIf a Beacon spell has been cast on the object, and its signature is known, the range of Locate Object is 1 mile per level with respects to the specific beacon.\n\nThe material component is a forked twig.\n\nThe reversal, obscure object, hides an object from location by spell, crystal ball, or similar means for eight hours.\n\nCreatures cannot be affected by this spell.\n\nThe material component is a chameleon skin.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 185,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 457,
      "name": "Magic Mouth",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a small bit of honeycomb",
      "range": "10 yds.",
      "aoe": "1 object",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When this spell is cast, the wizard imbues the chosen object with an enchanted mouth that suddenly appears and speaks its message when a specified event occurs.\n\nThe message, which must be of 25 words or less, can be in any language known by the spellcaster, and can be delivered over a period of one turn.\n\nThe mouth cannot speak magical spells or use command words.\n\nIt does, however, move to the words articulated - if it is placed upon a statue, the mouth of the statue would actually move and appear to speak.\n\nOf course, the magic mouth can be placed upon a tree, rock, door, or any other object, excluding intelligent members of the animal or vegetable kingdoms.\n\nThe spell functions when specific conditions are fulfilled, according to the command of the spellcaster.\n\nSome examples are to speak \"to the first creature that touches you,\" or \"to the first creature that passes within 30 feet.\" Commands can be as general or as detailed as desired, although only visual and audible triggers can be used, such as the following: \"Speak only when a venerable female human carrying a sack of groat clusters sits crosslegged within 1 foot.\" Such visual triggers can react to a character using the disguise ability.\n\nCommand range is 5 yards per level of the wizard, so a 6th-level wizard can command the magic mouth to speak at a maximum encounter range of 30 yards (\"Speak when a winged creature comes within 30 yards.\").\n\nThe spell lasts until the speak command can be fulfilled; thus, the spell duration is variable.\n\nA magic mouth cannot distinguish invisible creatures, alignments, level, Hit Dice, or class, except by external garb.\n\nIf desired, the effect can be keyed to a specific noise or spoken word.\n\nThe material component of this spell is a small bit of honeycomb.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 185,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 458,
      "name": "Maximillian's Earthen Grasp",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a miniature hand sculpted from clay,",
      "range": "10 yards + 10 yards/level",
      "aoe": "One creature",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "3 rounds + 1 round/level",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** causes an arm made of compacted soil to rise from the ground.\n\nThe spell must be cast on open turf, such as a grassy field or a dirt floor.\n\nThe earthen arm and hand (which are about the same size as a normal human limb) arise from the ground beneath one creature targeted by the caster.\n\nThe hand attempts to grasp the creature's leg.\n\nThe victim must attempt a saving throw; if successful, the hand sinks into the ground.\n\nEach round thereafter (until the spell ends or the target moves out of spell range), the hand has a 5% chance per level of the caster of reappearing beneath the targeted creature, at which time another saving throw is required.\n\nIf a saving throw is missed, the earthen limb firmly grasps and holds the creature in place.\n\nAn individual held by the hand suffers a movement rate of 0, Armor Class penalty of -2, and attack penalty of -2.\n\nAll Dexterity combat bonuses are negated.\n\nThe hand causes no physical damage to the victim.\n\nThe arm may be attacked by any creature, including the arm's victim.\n\nThe material component is a miniature hand sculpted from clay, which crumbles to dust when the spell is cast.",
      "source": "Tome of Magic",
      "page": 22,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 459,
      "name": "Melf's Acid Arrow",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Conjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a dart, powdered rhubarb leaf, and an adder's stomach",
      "range": "180 yds.",
      "aoe": "1 target",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "2d4",
      "description": "**By means of this spell**, the wizard creates a magical arrow that speeds to its target as if fired from the bow of a fighter of the same level as the wizard.\n\nNo modifiers for range, nonproficiency, or specialization are used.\n\nThe arrow has no attack or damage bonus, but it inflicts 2d4 points of acid damage (with saving throws for items on the target); there is no splash damage.\n\nFor every three levels that the caster has achieved, the acid, unless somehow neutralized, lasts for another round, inflicting another 2d4 points of damage each round.\n\nSo at 3rd-5th level, the acid lasts two rounds; at 6th-8th level, the acid lasts for three rounds, etc.\n\nThe material components of the spell are a dart, powdered rhubarb leaf, and an adder's stomach.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 186,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 460,
      "name": "Mirror Image",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "6-ft. radius",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "3 rds./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When a mirror image spell is invoked, the spellcaster causes from two to eight exact duplicates of himself to come into being around him.\n\nThese images do exactly what the wizard does.\n\nSince the spell causes a blurring and slight distortion when it is cast, it is impossible for opponents to be certain which are the illusions and which is the actual wizard.\n\nWhen an image is struck by a melee or missile attack, magical or otherwise, it disappears, but any other existing images remain intact until struck.\n\nThe images seem to shift from round to round, so that if the actual wizard is struck during one round, he cannot be picked out from among his images the next.\n\nTo determine the number of images that appear, roll 1d4 and add 1 for every three levels of experience the wizard has achieved, to a maximum of eight images.\n\nAt the end of the spell duration, all surviving images wink out.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 186,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 461,
      "name": "Misdirection",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "30 yds.",
      "aoe": "1 creature or object",
