      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** creates a wall or barrier of ominous shadow in any area within the spell range.\n\nThe wall of gloom does not obscure sight completely, but objects or creatures within the wall, or on its other side, are dim shadows that can barely be seen.\n\nCreatures attempting missile fire through the wall suffer a -2 penalty to their attack rolls.\n\nIn addition, the supernatural cold and darkness of the wall of gloom may cause creatures moving through the wall to recoil in fear.\n\nCreatures of 4 Hit Dice or less who enter the wall must make saving throw vs.\n\nspell or retreat for 1d3 rounds; creatures of 4+1 to 7 Hit Dice must save or hesitate for 1 round before entering the wall; and undead and creatures of 7+1 Hit Dice or more ignore the wall's fear effects.\n\nThe wall can take any shape the caster desires, as long as it is at least 10 feet high and 10 feet thick.\n\nThe material component is a bit of fleece from a black sheep and the eyelash of a revenant.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 143,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 481,
      "name": "Web",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Evocation",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a bit of spider web",
      "range": "5 yds./level",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "2 turns/level",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "A web spell creates a many-layered mass of strong, sticky strands similar to spider webs but far larger and tougher.\n\nThese masses must be anchored to two or more solid and diametrically opposed points - floor and ceiling, opposite walls, etc., or the web collapses upon itself and disappears.\n\nThe web spell covers a maximum area of eight 10' x 10' x 10' cubes and the webs must be at least 10 feet thick, so a mass 40 feet high, 20 feet wide, and 10 feet deep may be cast.\n\nCreatures caught within webs, or simply touching them, become stuck among the gluey fibers.\n\nAnyone in the area when the spell is cast must roll a saving throw vs.\n\nspell with a -2 penalty.\n\nIf the saving throw is successful, two things may have occurred.\n\nIf the creature has room to escape the area, then it is assumed to have jumped free.\n\nIf there is no room to escape, then the webs are only half strength.\n\nCreatures with less than 13 Strength (7 if the webs are half strength) are stuck until freed by another or until the spell wears off.\n\nMissile fire is generally ineffective against creatures trapped in webs.\n\nCreatures with Strengths between 13 and 17 can break through 1 foot of webs per round.\n\nCreatures with 18 or greater Strength can break through 2 feet of webs per round.\n\nIf the webs are at half strength, these rates are doubled.\n\n(Great mass equates to great strength in this case, and creatures of large mass hardly notice webs.) Strong and huge creatures can break through 10 feet of webs per round.\n\nFurthermore, the strands of a web spell are flammable.\n\nA magical flaming sword can slash them away as easily as a hand brushes away cobwebs.\n\nAny fire - torch, flaming oil, flaming sword, etc.\n\n- can set them alight and burn them away in a single round.\n\nAll creatures within flaming webs suffer 2d4 points of damage from the flames, but those free of the strands are not harmed.\n\nThe material component of this spell is a bit of spider web.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 189,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 482,
      "name": "Whispering Wind",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "1 mi./level",
      "aoe": "2-ft. radius",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**By means of this spell**, the wizard is able to either send a message or cause some desired sound effect.\n\nThe whispering wind can travel as many miles above ground as the spellcaster has levels of experience, to a specific location within range that is familiar to the wizard.\n\nThe whispering wind is as gentle and unnoticed as a zephyr until it reaches the location.\n\nIt then delivers its whisper-quiet message or other sound.\n\nNote that the message is delivered regardless of whether anyone is present to hear it.\n\nThe wind then dissipates.\n\nThe wizard can prepare the spell to bear a message of up to 25 words, cause the spell to deliver other sounds for one round, or merely have the whispering wind seem to be a faint stirring of the air that has a susurrant sound.\n\nHe can likewise cause the whispering wind to move as slowly as a mile per hour or as quickly as a mile per turn.\n\nWhen the spell reaches its objective, it swirls and remains until the message is delivered.\n\nAs with the magic mouth spell, no spells may be cast via the whispering wind.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 189,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 483,
      "name": "Wizard Lock",
      "level": "2",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "30 sq. ft./level",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "1 day / level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "A wizard lock spell cast upon a door, chest, or portal magically locks it.\n\nThe caster can freely pass his own lock without affecting it; otherwise, the wizard-locked door or object can be opened only by breaking in, by a successful dispel magic or knock spell, or by a wizard four or more levels higher than the one casting the spell.\n\nNote that the last two methods do not remove the wizard lock; they only negate it for a brief duration - about one turn.\n\nCreatures from other planes cannot burst a wizard lock as they can a held portal (see the hold portal spell).\n\nThis version of the spell may be dismissed with a gesture by the caster.\n\nUsing a ritual nearly identical to the Hold Portal spell, Wizard Lock too can be made permanent.\n\nIn addition to the costs of the Hold Portal ritual, an additional 1oz / 20 square feet is needed for a final symbol that requires no dexterity check, but an additional intelligence check.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 189,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 484,
      "name": "Alamir's Fundamental Breakdown",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Divination",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a wand cut",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "One item",
      "casting_time": "1 round",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "4d8/level",
      "description": "By casting this spell, the wizard learns what ingredients and formulas were used to create a chemical mixture or magical item.\n\nThe information instantly appears in the caster's mind but may be lost if the wizard cannot comprehend it.\n\nThe caster must roll an Intelligence check; if successful, the wizard understands the formula and retains it in his memory.\n\nIf the roll is missed, the caster cannot comprehend what he has learned and the information is immediately forgotten.\n\nIf the spell is cast a second time on the same substance, the spell automatically fails unless the wizard has advanced to the next experience level.\n\nThe caster's level determines the type of information gleaned: 5th Level: The type and quantity of ingredients and the preparation process required to produce a non-magical mixture are learned.\n\nFor example, the wizard could learn how to produce Greek fire or gunpowder, or could learn the recipe for something simple, like chocolate cake.\n\n9th Level: The wizard may learn the proper ingredients and formula for making a magical liquid (potion, scroll ink, etc.).\n\n14th Level: The caster may learn the formula for creating any type of magical object, excluding unique items and objects of extreme power (artifacts and relics).\n\nIn all cases, simply knowing the proper formula does not mean the wizard can successfully create the item or material.\n\nThe construction of alchemical mixtures and magical items is a time consuming and expensive undertaking.\n\n**This spell** has detrimental effects on the magical item analyzed.\n\nSingle-use items (potions, oils, etc.) are automatically destroyed; the spell consumes the item in the process of analyzing it.\n\nReusable magical items must make a saving throw vs.\n\ndisintegration.\n\nIf the saving throw is failed, Alamir's fundamental breakdown releases the magic of the item in an explosive blast, rendering it permanently nonmagical.\n\nThe caster suffers 4d8 points of damage from the explosion.\n\nThe material component is a wand cut from a 100-year-old oak tree.\n\nThe wand is used to touch the item in question, and vanishes in a puff of smoke when the spell is complete.",
      "source": "Tome of Magic",
      "page": 24,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 485,
      "name": "Alternate Reality",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a small, unmarked die",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "Creature touched",
      "casting_time": "3",
      "duration": "Instantaneous",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "With this spell, the caster creates a small variation in probabilities.\n\nThis variation lasts only a moment, but creates alternate results for one recent event.\n\nWhen the spell is cast, any one event attempted by the recipient during the previous round is recalculated, essentially allowing (or forcing) the creature to make new die rolls.\n\nOnly events that begin and end in a single round can be affected.\n\nOnly one die roll can be rerolled.\n\nIf the creature touched is a willing recipient, the player can choose which roll (the original or the new roll) affects him, more than likely picking the most successful.\n\nIf the creature is unwilling, he must redo the action.\n\nThe second result, whatever its outcome, cannot be changed.\n\nTypical uses of this spell include allowing a fighter to reroll an attack, forcing an opponent to reroll a saving throw, or allowing a wizard to reroll the damage caused by a fireball.\n\nThe material component is a small, unmarked die.",
      "source": "Tome of Magic",
      "page": 24,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 486,
      "name": "Bands of Sirellyn",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Conjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "three miniature bands of silver",
      "range": "40 yards",
      "aoe": "1 creature",
      "casting_time": "3",
      "duration": "1 turn + 1 rd./level",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "Once employed by the mysterious ancient wizard known as the Arcanamach, the mage Sirellyn rediscovered this forgotten dweomer many centuries after its last use.\n\nThe spell causes a number of shining metal bands to materialize out of the air, encircling and capturing a target of the caster's choice.\n\nThe victim is allowed a saving throw vs.\n\nspell to elude capture, with a -1 penalty per three caster levels (for example, -1 for a 4th to 6th level caster, -2 for a 7th to 9th level caster, -3 for a 10th to 12th level caster, and so on), since higher-level casters tend to conjure more bands in a denser pattern.\n\nAny creature of less than size G can be snared, but gargantuan monsters are simply too big to be restrained by the bands.\n\nThe spell requires three miniature bands of silver that are interlocked so that all three are connected.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 143,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 487,
      "name": "Blink",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "The caster",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**By means of this spell**, the wizard causes his material form to \"blink\" directly from one point to another at a random time and in a random direction.\n\nThis means that melee attacks against the wizard automatically miss if initiative indicates they fall after he has blinked.\n\nEach round the spell is in effect, the wizard rolls 2d8 to determine the timing of the blink - the result of the dice roll is used as the wizards initiative for that round.\n\nThe wizard disappears and instantaneously reappears 10 feet distant from his previous position.\n\n(Direction is determined by roll of ld8: 1 = right ahead, 2 = right, 3 = right behind, 4 = behind, 5 = left behind, 6 = left, 7 left ahead, 8 = ahead.) The caster cannot blink into a solid object; if such is indicated, reroll the direction.\n\nMovable objects of size and mass comparable to the caster are shoved aside when the caster blinks in.\n\nIf blinking is impossible except into a fixed, solid object, the caster is then trapped on the Ethereal plane.\n\nDuring each round that he blinks, the spellcaster can be attacked only by opponents who win initiative or by those who are able to strike both locations at once (e.g., with a breath weapon, fireball, or similar wide-area attack forms).\n\nOpponents with multiple attacks, or those operating under haste or similar effects, can often strike early enough to have at least one attack against the caster.\n\nIf the spellcaster holds off his attack (if any) until after the blink, the 2d8 delay until the blink is added to his normal ldl0 initiative roll (thus he probably attacks last in the round).\n\nOr the spellcaster can try to get his attack in before he blinks (he must announce his intent before rolling the 2d8 for blink timing and the 1d10 for initiative).\n\nIn this case, the caster compares the two dice rolls, hoping that his initiative roll is lower than his blink roll (the two rolls are not added if he is trying to attack before he blinks).\n\nIf so, he attacks according to his initiative roll, then blinks according to the blink roll.\n\nIf his blink roll is lower than his initiative roll, however, he blinks out, then he attacks in whatever direction he's facing (he must go through with his attack, even if he is facing in the wrong direction to affect anyone).",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 190,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 488,
      "name": "Clairaudience",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Divination",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a small horn of at least 100gp value",
      "range": "Unlimited",
      "aoe": "",
      "casting_time": "3",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "The clairaudience spell enables the wizard to concentrate upon some locale and hear in his mind any noise within a 60-foot radius of the spell's casting point.\n\nDistance is not a factor, but the locale must be known - a place familiar to the spellcaster or an obvious one (such as behind a door, around a corner, in a copse of trees, etc.).\n\nOnly sounds that are normally detectable by the wizard can be heard by use of this spell.\n\nLead sheeting or magical protections prevent the operation of the spell, and the wizard has some indication that the spell is so blocked.\n\nNote that it functions only on the wizard's current plane of existence.\n\nThe spell creates an invisible sensor that can be magically dispelled.\n\nThe material component of the spell is a small horn of at least 100gp value.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 190,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 489,
      "name": "Clairvoyance",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Divination",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a pinch of powdered pineal gland",
      "range": "Special",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "3",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "Similar to the clairaudience spell, the clairvoyance spell empowers the wizard to see in his mind whatever is within sight range from the spell locale chosen.\n\nDistance from the wizard is not a factor, but the locale must be known - familiar or obvious.\n\nFurthermore, light is a factor, as the spell does not enable the use of infravision or magical enhancements.\n\nIf the area is magically dark, only darkness is seen; if naturally pitch dark, only a 10-foot radius from the center of the spell's area of effect can be seen.\n\nOtherwise, the seeing extends to the normal vision range according to the prevailing light.\n\nLead sheeting or magical protection foils a clairvoyance spell, and the wizard has some indication that it is so blocked.\n\nThe spell creates an invisible sensor, similar to that created by a crystal ball spell, that can be dispelled.\n\nThe spell functions only on the wizards current plane of existence.\n\nThe material component is a pinch of powdered pineal gland.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 190,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 490,
      "name": "Delude",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "The caster",
      "casting_time": "3",
      "duration": "1 turn/level",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "By means of a delude spell, the wizard conceals his own alignment with that of any creature within a 30-foot radius at the time the spell is cast.\n\nThe creature must be of higher than animal intelligence for the spell to work; its own alignment remains unchanged.\n\nThe creature receives a saving throw vs.\n\nspell and, if successful, the delude spell fails.\n\nIf the spell is successful, any know alignment spell used against the caster discovers only the assumed alignment.\n\nNote that a detect good or detect evil also detects the assumed aura, if the aura is strong enough.\n\nThe creature whose aura has been assumed radiates magic, but the wizard radiates magic only to the creature whose alignment has been assumed.\n\nIf a delude spell is used in conjunction with a change self or alter self spell, the class of the wizard can be totally hidden, if he is clever enough to carry off the disguise.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 190,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 491,
      "name": "Dispel Magic",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Abjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "120 yds.",
      "aoe": "30-ft. cube",
      "casting_time": "3",
      "duration": "Instantaneous",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When a wizard casts this spell, it has a chance to neutralize or negate magic it comes in contact with, as follows:\n\n- **First**, it removes spells and spell-like effects (including device effects and innate abilities) from creatures or objects.  \n- **Second**, it disrupts the casting or use of these in the area of effect at the instant the dispel is cast.  \n- **Third**, it destroys magical potions (which are treated as 12th level for purposes of this spell).  \n\nEach effect or potion in the spell's area is checked to determine if it is dispelled. The caster can always dispel his own magic; otherwise the chance to dispel depends on the difference in level between the magical effect and the caster.\n\nThe base chance is **50% (11 or higher on 1d20 to dispel)**.  \nIf the caster is higher level than the creator of the effect to be dispelled, the difference is subtracted from the number needed on 1d20 to dispel (making it more likely to succeed).  \nIf the caster is of lower level, the difference is added to the number needed (making it less likely).  \nA roll of **20 always succeeds**, and a roll of **1 always fails**.\n\nA *dispel magic* spell does not affect a specially enchanted item (e.g., scroll, wand, rod, ring, weapon) unless cast directly on it. This renders the item **nonoperational for 1d4 rounds**.  \nItems carried by a creature gain the creature’s saving throw, otherwise they are affected automatically.  \nItems rendered nonoperational retain their physical properties.\n\n**Artifacts and relics** are not subject to this spell, though some of their effects may be, at the DM's option.\n\nThis spell is especially effective on charmed or magically compelled creatures. Spells or effects immune to *dispel magic* are noted in their descriptions. A failed dispel attempt cannot be retried until the caster gains a level.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 191,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 492,
      "name": "Feign Death",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Necromancy",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "Creature touched",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "1 hr.+ 1 turn/level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "By means of this spell, the caster (or any other creature whose levels of experience or Hit Dice do not exceed the wizard's own level) can be put into a **cataleptic state indistinguishable from death**.\n\nAlthough the subject can still **hear, smell, and perceive**, they have **no sensation or sight**.  \nThey are completely immune to **paralysis, poison, and energy-drain** effects, and **feel no pain**.  \nDamage taken is **halved**, and the subject makes **no reaction** to external stimuli.\n\n**Poison** introduced into the body will take effect **after** the spell ends, but the subject receives a **saving throw** at that time.\n\nOnly a **willing creature** can be affected.  \nThe caster may **end the effect at will**, or it may end with a **successful dispel**.  \nAfterward, it takes **one full round** for the subject's bodily functions to resume.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 191,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 493,
      "name": "Fireball",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Evocation",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a tiny ball of bat guano and sulphur",
      "range": "10 yds.+ 10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "20-ft. radius",
      "casting_time": "3",
      "duration": "Instantaneous",
      "save": "1/2",
      "damage": "1d6/level",
      "description": "A fireball is an **explosive burst of flame**, which detonates with a low roar and delivers damage based on the caster's level:  \n**1d6 points of damage per caster level**, up to **10d6 maximum**.\n\nThe fireball **conforms to the area’s shape**, filling roughly **33,000 cubic feet** (thirty-three 10′ × 10′ × 10′ cubes).\n\nIn addition to damage, the fireball **ignites combustible materials** and **melts soft metals** (gold, copper, etc.).  \nExposed items must make **saving throws vs. magical fire**. Items carried by creatures who succeed on their saving throws are **not affected**.\n\nThe wizard points and names a **distance and height**. A **streak of flame** flies out, exploding at that point unless it strikes a solid object earlier.  \nCreatures failing their save **take full damage**.  \nThose who succeed **take half damage** (rounded down).\n\n**Material component**: A tiny ball of **bat guano and sulphur**.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 191,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 494,
      "name": "Fireflow",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "A small paintbrush and a pot of pitch",
      "range": "30 yards",
      "aoe": "One fire source",
      "casting_time": "3",
      "duration": "1 round/level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "This spell allows a wizard to **control natural fires** by manipulating randomness and adjusting probabilities to cause them to **spread in a chosen direction**.\n\nThe wizard targets any fire within range. He may cause it to move or reshape **as long as the flames contact air**.  \nThe caster must **concentrate** for the spell to continue.  \nThe fire spreads at **50 square feet per turn**.\n\nFlames are **not limited by terrain**—they may spread over **water, ice, or other nonflammable surfaces**.  \nThe surface is not damaged, but **creatures and objects** touched by the flames **suffer normal damage** from the original fire source.\n\nFor example:\n- Fire spreading from a candle inflicts minor burns.\n- Fire from a bonfire causes severe burning.\n\n**Material components**: A **small paintbrush** and a **pot of pitch**.",
      "source": "Tome of Magic",
      "page": 25,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 495,
      "name": "Flame Arrow",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Conjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a drop of oil and a small piece of flint",
      "range": "30 yds.+ 10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "3",
      "duration": "1 rd",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "5d6",
      "description": "This spell has **two effects**:\n\n**1. Enchanting Ammunition**:\n- The wizard causes **arrows or bolts** to become **magical flaming missiles** for 1 round.\n- They must be **nocked and drawn (or cocked)** when the spell ends, or they burn up.\n- For every **5 caster levels**, up to 10 missiles may be affected.\n- Each hit does **normal weapon damage +1 fire damage**.\n- May ignite targets.\n\n**2. Fiery Bolts**:\n- The caster hurls **bolts** that deal **1d6 piercing + 4d6 fire damage**.\n- Targets that **save vs. spell** take **half fire damage**.\n- Gain 1 bolt per 5 levels (e.g., 2 at 10th, 3 at 15th).\n- Targets must be **within 20 yards** of each other and in front of the wizard.\n\n**Material components**: A **drop of oil** and a **small piece of flint**.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 192,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 496,
      "name": "Fly",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
