    {
      "id": 516,
      "name": "Phantom Steed",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Conjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "1 turn",
      "duration": "1 hr./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When this spell is cast, the wizard creates a quasi-real, horse-like creature.\n\nThe steed can be ridden only by the wizard who created it, or by any person for whom the wizard specifically creates such a mount.\n\nA phantom steed has a black head and body, gray mane and tail, and smoke-colored, insubstantial hooves that make no sound.\n\nIts eyes are milky-colored.\n\nIt does not fight, but all normal animals shun it and only monstrous ones will attack.\n\nThe mount has an Armor Class of 2 and 7 hit points, plus 1 per level of the caster.\n\nIf it loses all of its hit points, the phantom steed disappears.\n\nA phantom steed moves at a movement rate of 4 per level of the spellcaster, to a maximum movement rate of 48.\n\nIt has what seems to be a saddle and a bit and bridle.\n\nIt can bear its rider's weight, plus up to 10 pounds per caster level.\n\nThese mounts gain certain powers according to the level of the wizard who created them: 8th Level: The ability to pass over sandy, muddy, or even swampy ground without difficulty.\n\n10th Level: The ability to pass over water as if it were firm, dry ground.\n\n12th Level: The ability to travel in the air as if it were firm land, so chasms and the like can be crossed without benefit of a bridge.\n\nNote, however, that the mount cannot casually take off and fly; the movement must be between points of similar altitude.\n\n14th Level: The ability to perform as if it were a pegasus; it flies at a rate of 48 per round upon command.\n\nNote that a mount's abilities include those of lower levels; thus a 12th-level mount has the 8th-, 10th-, and 12th-level abilities.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 195,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 517,
      "name": "Protection from Amorphs",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Abjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a mixture of rare salts sprinkled",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "The caster",
      "casting_time": "3",
      "duration": "2 rds./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "This abjuration resembles the spells protection from vermin or protection from evil, but in this case the caster is protected from the attacks of any of the various amorphous monsters, including slimes, jellies, oozes, puddings, cubes, and slithering trackers.\n\nIn order to qualify as an amorphous creature, the monster must have an amorphous or fluid body, attack through acids or secretions of some kind, and be native to the Prime Material Plane (as opposed to extraplanar elementals and such creatures).\n\nThe monster cannot stand the touch of the barrier surrounding the protected character, and its natural attacks automatically fail.\n\nIf the monster has an innate ranged attack of any kind, these also fail.\n\nIf the protected character makes an attack against the monster, or if he forces the barrier against the monster, the spell ends and he is no longer protected.\n\nThe material component is a mixture of rare salts sprinkled in a small circle around the character to be protected.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 144,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 518,
      "name": "Protection From Evil, 10' Radius",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Abjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "powdered silver / powdered iron",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "10-foot-radius sphere around creature touched",
      "casting_time": "3",
      "duration": "2 rds./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "The globe of protection of this spell is identical in all respects to a protection from evil spell, except that it encompasses a much larger area and its duration is greater.\n\nThe effect is centered on and moves with the creature touched.\n\nAny protected creature within the circle can break the warding against enchanted or summoned monsters by meleeing them.\n\nIf a creature too large to fit into the area of effect is the recipient of the spell, the spell acts as a normal protection from evil spell for that creature only.\n\nTo complete this spell, the caster must trace a circle 20 feet in diameter using powdered silver.\n\nThe material component for the reverse is powdered iron.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 195,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 519,
      "name": "Protection From Normal Missiles",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Abjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a piece of tortoise or turtle shell",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "Creature touched",
      "casting_time": "3",
      "duration": "1 turn/level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**By means of this spell**, the wizard bestows total invulnerability to hurled and projected missiles such as arrows, axes, bolts, javelins, small stones, and spears.\n\nFurthermore, it causes a reduction of 1 from each die of damage (but no die inflicts less than 1 point of damage) inflicted by large or magical missiles, such as ballista missiles, catapult stones, hurled boulders, and magical arrows, bolts, javelins, etc.\n\nNote, however, that this spell does not convey any protection from such magical attacks as fireballs, lightning bolts, or magic missiles.\n\nThe material component of this spell is a piece of tortoise or turtle shell.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 196,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 520,
      "name": "Secret Page",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "powdered herring scales and either will o'wisp or boggart essence",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "1 page of any size, up to 2 ft. square",
      "casting_time": "1 turn",
      "duration": "Until dispelled",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When cast, a secret page spell alters the actual contents of a page so that they appear to be something entirely different.\n\nThus a map can be changed to become a treatise on burnishing ebony walking sticks.\n\nThe text of a spell can be altered to show a ledger page or even another form of spell.\n\nConfuse languages and explosive runes spells may be cast upon the secret page, but a comprehend languages spell cannot reveal the secret page's contents.\n\nThe caster is able to reveal the original contents by speaking a command word, perusing the actual page, and then returning it to its secret page form.\n\nThe caster can also remove the spell by double repetition of the command word.\n\nOthers noting the dim magic of a page with this spell cloaking its true contents can attempt to dispel magic, but if it fails, the page is destroyed.\n\nA true seeing spell does not reveal the contents unless cast in combination with a comprehend languages spell.\n\nAn erase spell can destroy the writing.\n\nThe material components are powdered herring scales and either Will O'Wisp or boggart essence.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 196,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 521,
      "name": "Sepia Snake Sigil",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Conjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "100 gp worth of powdered amber, a scale from any snake, and a pinch of mushroom spores",
      "range": "5 yds.",
      "aoe": "1 sigil",
      "casting_time": "3",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When this spell is cast, a small written symbol appears in the text of any written work.\n\nWhen read, the so-called sepia snake springs into being and strikes at the nearest living creature (but does not attack the wizard who cast the spell).\n\nIts attack is made as if it were a monster with Hit Dice equal to the level of the wizard who cast the spell.\n\nIf it strikes successfully, the victim is engulfed in a shimmering amber field of force, frozen and immobilized until released, either at the caster's command, by a successful dispel magic spell, or until a time equal to 1d4 days + 1 day per caster level has elapsed.\n\nUntil then, nothing can get at the victim, move the shimmering force surrounding him, or otherwise affect him.\n\nThe victim does not age, grow hungry, sleep, or regain spells while in this state.\n\nHe is not aware of his surroundings.\n\nIf the sepia snake misses its target, it dissipates in a flash of brown light, with a loud noise and a puff of dun-colored smoke that is 10 feet in diameter and lasts for one round.\n\nThe spell cannot be detected by normal observation, and detect magic reveals only that the entire text is magical.\n\nA dispel magic can remove it; an erase spell destroys the entire page of text.\n\nIt can be cast in combination with other spells that hide or garble text.\n\nThe components for the spell are 100 gp worth of powdered amber, a scale from any snake, and a pinch of mushroom spores.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 196,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 522,
      "name": "Slow",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a drop of molasses",
      "range": "90 yds.+ 10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "40-ft. cube, 1 creature/level",
      "casting_time": "3",
      "duration": "3 rds.+ 1 rd./level",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "A slow spell causes affected creatures to move and attack at half their normal rates.\n\nIt negates a haste spell or equivalent, but does not otherwise affect magically speeded or slowed creatures.\n\nSlowed creatures have an Armor Class penalty of +4 AC, an attack penalty of -4, and all Dexterity combat bonuses are negated.\n\nThe magic affects a number of creatures equal to the spellcaster's level, if they are within the area of effect chosen by the wizard (i.e., a 40-foot cubic volume centered as called for by the caster).\n\nThe creatures are affected from the center of the spell outward.\n\nThe material component of this spell is a drop of molasses.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 196,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 523,
      "name": "Solvent of Corrosion",
      "level": "3",
      "school": "Conjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a mixture of vinegar, water, and a drop of black dragon acid",
      "range": "10 yards",
      "aoe": "1 sq. ft./level",
      "casting_time": "3",
      "duration": "3 rounds",
      "save": "1/2",
      "damage": "Special",
      "description": "**This spell** conjures a corrosive, acidic slime of horrid strength on one surface or creature within the spell's range.\n\nUp to one square foot of surface area per caster level can be affected, so a 5th-level caster can affect 5 square feet - enough to create a 2-foot by 3-foot hole in a door or wall, or thoroughly drench a man-sized creature.\n\nThe acid eats through 6 inches of wood, leather, or bone, 4 inches of stone, or 1 inch of metal each round.\n\nAgainst monsters composed of stone, metal or wood, the solvent inflicts 1d3 points of damage per caster level in the first round, 1d2 per caster level in the second round, and 1 per two caster levels in the third and final round.\n\nTherefore, a 10th-level wizard who strikes a Treant with solvent of corrosion inflicts 10d3, then 10d2 and finally 5 points of damage.\n\nEach round, the victim is allowed a saving throw vs.\n\nspell for half damage.\n\nAgainst flesh, the solvent is much less effective; it is caustic and burns painfully, inflicting 1 point of damage per caster level in the first round, but no further damage in the second or third round.\n\nHowever, the burning in the following rounds does inflict a -2 penalty to the victim's attacks while the solvent is active.\n\nThe solvent is extremely likely to cause extensive damage to the victim's armor and equipment; item saving throws vs.\n\nacid may apply at the DM's discretion.\n\nIf the armor or equipment is magical in nature, then the saving throws is made with the usual bonuses allowed to the magical item.\n\nThe great alchemist Vandarien developed his solvent to dissolve iron grates, stone and woodwork traps, and other such hazards.\n\nThe solvent's effectiveness against mineral or wood-based creatures was a mere side effect of his research.\n\nThe material component of this spell is a mixture of vinegar, water, and a drop of black dragon acid.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 144,
      "reversible": false
    },
