      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** is similar to the invisibility spell, but the recipient is able to attack, either by missile discharge, melee combat, or spellcasting, and remain unseen.\n\nNote, however, that there are sometimes telltale traces, a shimmering, so that an observant opponent can attack the invisible spell recipient.\n\nThese traces are only noticeable when specifically looked for (after the invisible character has made his presence known).\n\nAttacks against the invisible character suffer -4 penalties to the attack rolls, and the invisible character's saving throws are made with a +4 bonus.\n\nHigh Hit Dice creatures that might notice invisible opponents will notice a creature under this spell as if they had 2 fewer Hit Dice (they roll saving throws vs.\n\nspell; success indicates they spot the character).",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 203,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 557,
      "name": "Improved Strength",
      "level": "4",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a strand of hair from a giant",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "Creature touched",
      "casting_time": "4",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "By casting this spell, the wizard can empower a creature with superhuman strength.\n\nUnlike the 2nd-level strength spell, improved strength allows the recipient of the spell to ignore race or class restrictions on his maximum Strength score, possibly reaching scores as high as 25.\n\nThe exact amount of strength gained varies by the recipient’s class group: Class Strength Gain* Warrior 1d8+4 (max 25) Priest 1d6+4 (max 23) Rogue 1d6+4 (max 23) Wizard 1d4+4 (max 21) * Count each percentile bracket of exceptional strength as one point; the strength gain proceeds as 18, 18/01, 18/51, 18/76, 18/91, 18/00, 19, and so on.\n\nEven if the recipient is not a warrior, he gains all the benefits of an exceptional Strength category; for example, if a thief with a Strength of 14 gained 7 points, he would possess a Strength of 18/76 for the duration of the spell.\n\nIn addition to the attack and damage bonus, increased chance to open doors or bend bars, and increased carrying capacity, the spell recipient may temporarily gain the ability to throw boulders as a giant of equivalent Strength, as shown below: Strength Giant Type Range Damage 19 Hill giant 80 yards 1d6 20 Stone giant 100 yards 1d8 21 Frost giant 100 yards 1d8 22 Fire giant 120 yards 1d8 23 Cloud giant 140 yards 1d10 24 Storm giant 160 yards 1d12 25 Titan 200 yards 1d20 When the spell ends, the recipient is struck by intense exhaustion; he can do nothing except rest for 1d3 full turns to recover his strength.\n\nThe material component is a strand of hair from a giant.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 145,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 558,
      "name": "Leomund's Secure Shelter",
      "level": "4",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a square chip of stone",
      "range": "20 yds.",
      "aoe": "30 sq. ft./level",
      "casting_time": "4 turns",
      "duration": "1d4+1 hr.+ 1 hr./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** enables the wizard to magically call into being a sturdy cottage or lodge, made of material that is common in the area where the spell is cast - stone, timber, or (at worst) sod.\n\nThe floor area of the lodging is 30 square feet per level of the spellcaster, and the surface is level, clean, and dry.\n\nIn all respects the lodging resembles a normal cottage, with a sturdy door, two or more shuttered windows, and a small fireplace.\n\nWhile the lodging is secure against winds of up to 70 miles per hour, it has no heating or cooling source (other than natural insulation qualities).\n\nTherefore it must be heated as a normal dwelling, and extreme heat adversely affects it and its occupants.\n\nThe dwelling does, however, provide considerable security otherwise, as it is as strong as a normal stone building, regardless of its material composition, resists flames and fire as if it were stone, and is impervious to normal missiles (but not the sort cast by siege machinery or giants).\n\nThe door, shutters, and even chimney are secure against intrusion, the former two being wizard locked and the latter being secured by a top grate of iron and a narrow flue.\n\nIn addition, these three areas are protected by an alarm spell.\n\nLastly, an unseen servant is called up to provide service to the spellcaster.\n\nThe inside of the shelter contains rude furnishings as desired by the spellcaster - up to eight bunks, a trestle table and benches, as many as four chairs or eight stools, and a writing desk.\n\nThe material components of this spell are a square chip of stone, crushed lime, a few grains of sand, a sprinkling of water, and several splinters of wood.\n\nThese must be augmented by the components of the alarm and unseen servant spells if these benefits are to be included (string and silver wire and a small bell).",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 203,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 559,
      "name": "Lesser Geas",
      "level": "4",
      "school": "Enchantment",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": false,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "10 yards",
      "aoe": "1 creature",
      "casting_time": "2",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**By means of this spell**, the wizard places a magical command upon a creature of 7 Hit Dice or less to carry out some service, undertake a task, or refrain from some action or course of activity.\n\nThe caster specifies the conditions of the lesser geas when he casts the spell; the victim must be intelligent, conscious, able to understand the caster, and not under the influence of any spells or effects that affect or control its mind.\n\nThe lesser geas cannot compel a creature to kill itself or perform acts that will result in certain death, although the wizard can use the spell to coerce the subject into almost any other nondestructive course of action.\n\nThe victim is entitled to a saving throw vs.\n\nspell to avoid the lesser geas, but suffers a -2 penalty on its save if the wizard is of higher level or Hit Dice, or a -4 penalty if the wizard is more than twice the victim’s level or Hit Dice.\n\nThe wizard must be careful in the wording of his lesser geas since the casting and fulfillment are tricky.\n\nThe subject should be given a tangible, achievable goal, with clear courses of action available to him.\n\n\"Climb that mountain!\" or \"Tear that mountain down rock by rock!\" are legitimate geases, but a geas such as \"Become a mountain!\" is just not specific enough to work.\n\nSimilar to the 6th-level spell geas, the lesser geas compels the subject to obey the wizard's command.\n\nIf the geased creature fails to follow the wizard's instructions, it will grow sick-each week that passes, the creature loses one point from each ability score, 1 hit point per Hit Die, and suffers a cumulative -1 penalty to attack rolls and saving throws.\n\nThese penalties cannot reduce an ability score to less than 3, reduce a creature to less than 1 hit point per Hit Die, or reduce its attacks and saves by more than 4 points.\n\nThe lesser geas can be countermanded by a remove curse spell, or a limited wish or wish.\n\nHowever, if the subject entertains thoughts of removing the lesser geas, it will protect itself by giving the subject a warning headache.\n\nIf the subject persists, then the sickness will begin.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 146,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 560,
      "name": "Locate Creature",
      "level": "4",
      "school": "Divination",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a bit of a blood hounds fur",
      "range": "50 yards/level",
      "aoe": "One creature",
      "casting_time": "5",
      "duration": "1 turn/level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** is similar to the 2nd-level locate object spell.\n\nInstead of finding an inanimate object, however, it allows the wizard to find a creature.\n\nThe wizard casts the spell, slowly turns, and is able to sense the direction of the person or creature, provided the subject is within range.\n\nThe wizard learns how far away the creature is and in what direction it is moving (if at all).\n\n**This spell** can locate a general species of creature (a horse or umber hulk, for instance) or can be used to find a specific individual.\n\nThe wizard must have physically seen the individual or the type of creature at least once from a distance of no more than 10 yards.\n\nUnlike locate object, this spell is not blocked by lead.\n\nIt is blocked, however, by running water (such as a river or stream).\n\nObjects cannot be found through use of this spell.\n\nThe material component is a bit of a bloodhounds fur.",
      "source": "Tome of Magic",
      "page": 29,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 561,
      "name": "Magic Mirror",
      "level": "4",
      "school": "Divination",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "the eye of a hawk, an eagle, or even a roc, and nitric acid, copper, and zinc",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "1 hr.",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**By means of this spell**, the wizard changes a normal mirror into a scrying device similar to a crystal ball.\n\nThe details of the use of such a scrying device are found in the DMG under the description for the crystal ball.\n\nThe mirror used must be of finely wrought and highly polished silver of a minimum cost not less than 1,000gp.\n\nThis mirror is not harmed by casting the spell, but the other material components - the eye of a hawk, an eagle, or even a roc, and nitric acid, copper, and zinc - are used up.\n\nThe following spells can be cast through a magic mirror: comprehend languages, read magic, tongues, and infravision.\n\nThe following spells have a 5% chance per level of the caster of operating correctly: detect magic, detect good or evil, and message.\n\nThe base chances for the subject to detect any crystal ball-like spell is listed in the crystal ball entry in the DMG (see the \"Miscellaneous Magic\" section).",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 203,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 562,
      "name": "Mask of Death",
      "level": "4",
      "school": "Necromancy",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "A drop of doppleganger",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "One creature",
      "casting_time": "1 round",
      "duration": "1 hour/level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "By casting this spell, a wizard can change a corpse's features to make it appear to be someone else.\n\nThe caster must possess an accurate portrait of the individual to be duplicated, or must have a clear mental image of the person based on personal experience.\n\nIf animate dead is cast on the body, it can be animated to become a zombie that looks exactly like the copied person.\n\nThe double is a mindless automaton, however, having all the characteristics of a normal zombie.\n\n**This spell** may be cast on a creature that has already become a zombie.\n\nThe wizard must successfully touch the zombie in combat, unless the zombie is controlled by the caster.\n\nThe material component of this spell is a drop of doppelganger's blood.",
      "source": "Tome of Magic",
      "page": 29,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 563,
      "name": "Massmorph",
      "level": "4",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a handful of bark chips",
      "range": "10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "10 ft. cube/level",
      "casting_time": "4",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When this spell is cast upon willing creatures of man-size or smaller, up to 10 such creatures per level of the caster can be magically altered to appear as trees of any sort.\n\nThus a company of creatures can be made to appear as a copse, grove, or orchard.\n\nFurthermore, these massmorphed creatures can be passed through - and even touched - by other creatures without revealing their true nature.\n\nNote, however, that blows to the creature-trees cause damage, and blood can be seen.\n\nCreatures to be massmorphed must be within the spell's area of effect and unwilling creatures are not affected.\n\nAffected creatures remain unmoving but aware, subject to normal sleep requirements, and able to see, hear, and feel for as long as the spell is in effect.\n\nThe spell persists until the caster commands it to cease or until a dispel magic spell is cast upon the creatures.\n\nCreatures left in this state for extended periods are subject to insects, weather, disease, fire, and other natural hazards.\n\nThe material component of this spell is a handful of bark chips from the type of tree the creatures are to become.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 203,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 564,
      "name": "Minor Creation",
      "level": "4",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a tiny piece of matter",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "1 turn",
      "duration": "1 day / level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** enables the wizard to create an item of non-living, vegetable nature - soft goods, rope, wood, etc.\n\nThe caster actually pulls wisps of material of the plane of Shadow from the air and weaves them into the desired item.\n\nThe volume of the item created cannot exceed one cubic foot per level of the spellcaster.\n\nThe item remains in existence for only as long as the spell's duration.\n\nThe spellcaster must have at least a tiny piece of matter of the same type of item he plans to create by means of the minor creation spell - a bit of twisted hemp to create rope, a splinter of wood to create a door, and so forth.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 203,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 565,
      "name": "Minor Globe of Invulnerability",
      "level": "4",
      "school": "Abjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a glass or crystal bead",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "5-ft. radius sphere",
      "casting_time": "4",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** creates an immobile, faintly shimmering magical sphere around the caster that prevents any 1st-, 2nd-, or 3rd-level spell effects from penetrating (i.e., the area of effect of any such spells does not include the area of the minor globe of invulnerability).\n\nThis includes innate abilities and effects from devices.\n\nHowever, any type of spell can be cast out of the magical sphere, and these pass from the caster of the globe to their subject without affecting the minor globe.\n\nFourth and higher level spells are not affected by the globe.\n\nThe globe can be brought down by a successful dispel magic spell.\n\nThe caster can leave and return to the globe without penalty.\n\nNote that spell effects are not actually disrupted by the globe unless cast directly through or into it: The caster would still see a mirror image created by a wizard outside the globe.\n\nIf that wizard then entered the globe, the images would wink out, to reappear when the wizard exited the globe.\n\nLikewise, a wizard standing in the area of a light spell would still receive sufficient light for vision, even though that part of the light spell volume in the globe would not be luminous.\n\nThe material component of the spell is a glass or crystal bead that shatters at the expiration of the spell.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 203,
      "reversible": false
    },
