      "duration": "ld4 rounds + 1 round/level",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When this spell is cast, the illusionist transforms one creature or a specified amount of nonliving material into shadow, making it insubstantial.\n\nThus, a door could be turned to shadow and entered.\n\nThe maximum amount of inanimate material that may be transformed is one cubic foot per level of the caster.\n\nUnwilling creatures are allowed a saving throw to resist the shadowy transformation.\n\nMagical items and the magical effects of spells (such as Bigby's forceful hand or a wall of stone ) cannot be affected.\n\nA transformed creature and all its gear become insubstantial.\n\nThe creature can pass through small holes, narrow openings, and the smallest cracks.\n\nThe creature cannot fly without additional magic.\n\nNo form of attack is possible when in shadow form except against creatures that exist on the Ethereal plane.\n\nIn this case, all attacks are normal; however, the shadowy creature may be harmed only by magical weapons of +1 or greater or by creatures able to affect those struck only by magical weapons.\n\nSpells and special attacks have normal effects.\n\nMost undead creatures will ignore a creature in shadow form, believing it to be a wraith or specter; however, liches and powerful undead may save vs.\n\nspell with a -4 penalty to recognize the spell.\n\nA successful dispel magic spell forces the creature in shadow form back to normal form.",
      "source": "Tome of Magic",
      "page": 38,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 672,
      "name": "Lower Water",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a small vial of dust.",
      "range": "80 yds.",
      "aoe": "10-ft./level square",
      "casting_time": "1 turn",
      "duration": "5 rds./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "The wizard casting a lower water spell causes water or similar fluid in the area of effect to sink away.\n\nThe water can be lowered up to 2 feet for every experience level of the wizard, to a minimum depth of 1 inch.\n\nThe water is lowered within a square area whose sides are 10 feet long per caster level.\n\nThus, a 12th-level wizard affects a volume of 24 feet x 120 feet x 120 feet, a 13th-level caster a volume of 26 feet x 130 feet x 130 feet, and so on.\n\nIn extremely large and deep bodies of water, such as deep ocean, the spell creates a whirlpool that sweeps ships and similar craft downward, putting them at risk and rendering them unable to leave by normal movement for the duration of the spell.\n\nWhen cast on water elementals and other water-based creatures, this spell acts as a slow spell: The creature moves at half speed and makes half the number of attacks each round.\n\nIt has no effect on other creatures.\n\nThe material component of this spell is a small vial of dust.\n\nIts reverse, raise water, causes water or similar fluids to return to their highest natural level: spring flood, high tide, etc.\n\nThis can make fords impassable, float grounded ships, and may even sweep away bridges, at the DM's option.\n\nIt negates lower water and vice versa.\n\nThe material component of the raise water spell is a small vial of water.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 227,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 673,
      "name": "Mass Suggestion",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Enchantment",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": false,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a snake's tongue",
      "range": "30 yds.",
      "aoe": "1 creature/level",
      "casting_time": "6",
      "duration": "4 turns + 4 turns/level",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "The mass suggestion spell enables the wizard to influence the actions of one or more chosen creatures in the same way as the suggestion spell.\n\nUp to one creature per experience level of the caster can be influenced, provided that all subject creatures are within the 30-yard range.\n\nUndead are not subject to this spell.\n\nThe suggestion must be reasonably worded and understood by the creatures, and must be the same for all hearing it.\n\nCreatures successfully saving vs.\n\nspell are unaffected.\n\nSaving throws against the spell suffer a penalty of -1, and if a single creature is to be affected, its saving throw suffers a -4 penalty.\n\nNote that a very reasonable mass suggestion can cause the saving throw to be made with an additional penalty (such as -1, -2, etc.), at the discretion of your DM.\n\nA mass suggestion can continue in effect for a considerable duration, at the DM's discretion.\n\nConditions that will trigger a special action can also be specified; if the condition is not met before the spell expires, the action will not be performed.\n\nThe material components of this spell are a snake's tongue and either a bit of honeycomb or a drop of sweet oil.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 227,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 674,
      "name": "Mislead",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": false,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "10 yds.",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**When a mislead spell is cast** by the wizard, he actually creates an illusory double at the same time that he is cloaked by improved invisibility magic (see the 4th-level spell).\n\nThe wizard is then free to go elsewhere while his double seemingly moves away.\n\nThe spell enables the illusion of the wizard to speak and gesture as if it were real, and there are full olfactory and touch components as well.\n\nA true seeing spell or a gem of seeing will reveal the illusion for what it is.\n\nA detect invisibility or true seeing spell or items such as a gem of seeing or robe of eyes can detect the invisible wizard (see the 5th-level wizard spell shadow door).",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 227,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 675,
      "name": "Monster Summoning IV",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Conjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a tiny bag and a small candle",
      "range": "Special",
      "aoe": "60-yd. radius",
      "casting_time": "6",
      "duration": "5 rds. + 1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** is much like the 3rd-level spell monster summoning I, except that this spell summons 1d3 4th-level monsters.\n\nThese appear within the spell's area of effect and attack the caster's opponents, until he commands them to cease, the spell duration expires, or the monsters are slain.\n\nThese creatures do not check morale; they vanish when slain.\n\nIf no opponent exists to fight, summoned monsters can, if the wizard can communicate with them, and if they are physically capable, perform other services for the summoning wizard.\n\nThe material components of this spell are a tiny bag and a small (not necessarily lit) candle.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 228,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 676,
      "name": "Mordenkainen's Lucubration",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "The caster",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "Instantaneous",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "By use of this spell, the wizard is able to instantly recall any 1st- through 5th-level spell he has used during the past 24 hours.\n\nThe spell must have been memorized and actually used during that time period.\n\nMordenkainen's lucubration allows the recovery of only one spell.\n\nIf the recalled spell requires material components, these must be provided by the caster; the recovered spell is not usable until the material components are available.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 228,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 677,
      "name": "Move Earth",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a mixture of soils",
      "range": "10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "Special",
      "duration": "Permanent",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When cast, the move earth spell moves dirt (clay, loam, sand) and its other components.\n\nThus, embankments can be collapsed, hillocks moved, dunes shifted, etc.\n\nHowever, in no event can rock prominences be collapsed or moved.\n\nThe area to be affected dictates the casting time; for every 40 yard x 40 yard surface area and 10 feet of depth, one turn of casting time is required.\n\nThe maximum area that can be affected is 240 yards x 240 yards, which takes four hours.\n\nIf terrain features are to be moved--as compared to simply caving in banks or walls of earth--it is necessary that an earth elemental be subsequently summoned to assist.\n\nAll spell casting or summoning must be completed before any effects occur.\n\nAs any summoned earth elemental will perform most of its work underground, it is unlikely that it will be intercepted or interrupted.\n\nShould this occur, however, the movement of the earth requiring its services must be stopped until the elemental is once again available.\n\nShould the elemental be slain or dismissed, the move earth spell is limited to collapsing banks or walls of earth.\n\nThe spell cannot be used for tunneling and is generally too slow to trap or bury creatures; its primary use is for digging or filling moats or for adjusting terrain contours before a battle.\n\nThe material components for this spell are a mixture of soils (clay, loam, sand) in a small bag and an iron blade.\n\nNote: **This spell** does not violently break the surface of the ground.\n\nInstead, it creates wavelike crests and troughs, with the earth reacting with glacierlike fluidity until the desired result is achieved.\n\nTrees, structures, rock formations, etc.\n\nare relatively unaffected, save for changes in elevation and relative topography.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 228,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 678,
      "name": "Otiluke's Freezing Sphere",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Abjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "1,000-gp diamond.",
      "range": "Special",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "6",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "Otiluke's Freezing Sphere is a multipurpose spell of considerable power.\n\nIf the caster opts, he may create any of the following: A) Frigid globe.\n\nA small globe of matter at absolute zero temperature that spreads upon contact with water, or a liquid that is principally water, freezing it to a depth of 6 inches over an area equal to 100 square feet per level of the spellcaster.\n\nThis ice lasts for one round per level of the caster.\n\nThe material component is a thin sheet of crystal about an inch square.\n\nB) Cold ray.\n\nThe spell can be used as a thin ray of cold that springs from the caster's hand to a distance of 10 yards per level of the wizard; this ray inflicts 1d4+2 points of damage per level of the caster upon the first creature struck.\n\nA saving throw vs.\n\nspell is applicable; all damage is negated if it is successful (as the ray is so narrow a save indicates it missed).\n\nIf the first creature is missed, the path of the ray is plotted to its full distance, and anything else in its path must save (if applicable) or suffer appropriate damage.\n\nThe material component is a white sapphire of not less than 1,000gp value.\n\nC) Globe of cold.\n\nThis creates a small globe about the size of a sling stone, cool to the touch, but not harmful.\n\nThis globe can be hurled, either by hand to a distance of 40 yards (considered short range), or as a sling bullet.\n\nThe globe shatters upon impact, inflicting 6d6 points of cold damage upon all creatures within a 10-foot radius (one-half damage if a saving throw vs.\n\nspell is successful).\n\nUse the Grenadelike Missile Table in the Dungeon Master Guide to find where misses strike.\n\nNote that if the globe is not thrown or slung within one round per level of the spellcaster, it shatters and causes cold damage as stated above.\n\nThis timed effect can be employed against pursuers, although it can prove hazardous to the spellcaster and his associates as well.\n\nThe material component is a 1,000gp diamond.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 228,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 679,
      "name": "Part Water",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "two small sheets of crystal or glass.",
      "range": "10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "20 ft. x3 ft./level x 30 ft./level",
      "casting_time": "1 turn",
      "duration": "5 rds./level",
      "save": "1/2",
      "damage": "4d8/level",
      "description": "By employing a part water spell, the wizard is able to cause water or similar liquid to move apart, thus forming a 20-foot-wide trough.\n\nThe depth and length of the trough are dependent upon the level of the wizard, and a trough 3 feet deep by 10 yards long is created per level.\n\nFor example, at 12th level the wizard would part water 36 feet deep by 20 feet wide by 120 yards long.\n\nThe trough remains as long as the spell lasts or until the wizard who cast it opts to end its effects.\n\nIf cast under water, this spell creates an air cylinder of appropriate length and diameter.\n\nIf cast directly on a water elemental or other water-based creature, the creature receives 4d8 damage and must roll a successful saving throw vs.\n\nspell or flee in panic for 3d4 rounds.\n\nThe material components for the spell are two small sheets of crystal or glass.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 229,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 680,
      "name": "Permanent Illusion",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a bit of fleece",
      "range": "10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "20-ft. cube +10-ft. cube/level",
      "casting_time": "6",
      "duration": "Permanent",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When this spell is cast, the wizard creates an illusion with visual, auditory, olfactory, and thermal elements.\n\nThe spell can create the illusion of any object, creature, or force, as long as it is within the boundaries of the spell's area of effect.\n\nIt affects all creatures that view the illusion, even to the extent of them suffering damage from falling into an illusory pit full of sharp spikes.\n\nCreatures that attempt to disbelieve the illusion gain a saving throw vs.\n\nspell and, if successful, they see it for what it is and add +4 bonuses to associates' saving throws, if this knowledge can be communicated effectively.\n\nCreatures not sensing the spell effect are immune until they become aware of it.\n\nThe permanent illusion is subject to a dispel magic spell, of course.\n\nThe material component of the spell is a bit of fleece.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 229,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 681,
      "name": "Programmed Illusion",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a bit of fleece.",
      "range": "10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "20-ft. cube +10-ft. cube/level",
      "casting_time": "6",
      "duration": "Special",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "u",
      "description": "This spell creates an **illusion of an event or object** that appears completely **real** in every way, including sound, shape, smell, and texture.  \nThe illusion can even have **specific sounds, smells, and touch sensations**, but not independent movement.\n\nThe duration depends on the illusion's complexity:\n- **Minor illusion** lasts 10 minutes.\n- **Major illusion** lasts 1 hour.\n- **Complex illusion** lasts 1 hour per level of the caster.\n\nThe spellcaster must specify the **illusion's limits**. It can simulate a whole scene, object, or being but must be realistic in that context. **Small actions or moving objects cannot be simulated** unless specifically listed (such as invisible movements).  \n**Caster’s level** determines the complexity of the illusion.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 229,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 682,
      "name": "Project Image",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a small replica (doll) of the wizard.",
      "range": "10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "6",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**By means of this spell**, the wizard creates a nonmaterial duplicate of himself, projecting it to any spot within spell range.\n\nThis image performs actions decided by the wizard--walking, speaking, spellcasting--conforming to the actual actions of the wizard unless he concentrates on making it act differently (in which case the wizard is limited to half movement and no attacks).\n\nThe image can be dispelled only by means of a successful dispel magic spell (or upon command from the spellcaster); attacks pass harmlessly through it.\n\nThe image must be within view of the wizard projecting it at all times, and if his sight is obstructed, the spell is broken.\n\nNote that if the wizard is invisible at the time the spell is cast, the image is also invisible until the caster's invisibility ends, though the wizard must still be able to see the image (by means of a detect invisibility spell or other method) to maintain the spell.\n\nIf the wizard uses dimension door, teleport, plane shift, or a similar spell that breaks his line of vision, the project image spell ends.\n\nThe material component of this spell is a small replica (doll) of the wizard.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 229,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 683,
      "name": "Repulsion",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Abjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a pair of small magnetized iron bars",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "10 ft./level x 10 ft.",
      "casting_time": "6",
      "duration": "1 round/2 levels",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When this spell is cast, the wizard is able to cause all creatures in the path of the area of effect to move directly away from his person.\n\nRepulsion occurs at the speed of the creature attempting to move toward the spellcaster.\n\nThe repelled creature continues to move away for a complete round even if this takes it beyond spell range.\n\nThe caster can designate a new direction each round, but use of this power counts as the caster's principal action in the round.\n\nThe caster can, of course, choose to do something else instead of using the repulsion attack.\n\nThe material component for this spell is a pair of small magnetized iron bars attached to two small canine statuettes, one ivory and one ebony.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 230,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 684,
      "name": "Shades",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Illusion",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "30 yds.",
      "aoe": "20-ft. cube",
      "casting_time": "6",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** is related to the shadow monsters and demishadow monsters spells.\n\nThe shades spell uses material from the Demiplane of Shadow to form semireal illusions of one or more monsters, up to 1 Hit Die per caster level.\n\nAll shades created by one spell must be of the same sort, and they have 60% of the hit point total the real creatures would have.\n\nThose who view the shades and fail their saving throws vs.\n\nspell believe the illusion.\n\nThe shades perform as the real monsters with respect to Armor Class and attack forms.\n\nSpecial attack forms such as petrification or level drain do not actually occur, but a subject who believes the shades are real will react appropriately, until the illusion is countered by a dispel magic spell or the condition is countered by a heal spell.\n\nThose who roll successful saving throws see the shades as transparent images superimposed on vague shadowy forms.\n\nThese are Armor Class 6 and cause only 60% of the true monsters' normal melee damage.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 230,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 685,
      "name": "Stone to Flesh",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "lime, water, and earth.",
      "range": "10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "1 creature",
      "casting_time": "6",
      "duration": "Permanent",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "The stone to flesh spell turns any sort of stone into flesh.\n\nIf the recipient stone object was formerly living, this spell restores life (and goods), although the survival of the creature is subject to the usual system shock survival roll.\n\nAny formerly living creature, regardless of size, can be thus returned to flesh.\n\nOrdinary stone can be turned to flesh in a volume of 9 cubic feet per level of experience of the spellcaster.\n\nSuch flesh is inert, lacking a vital life force, unless a life force or magical energy is available (for example, this spell would turn a stone golem into a flesh golem, but an ordinary statue would become a body).\n\nIf cast upon stone, the wizard can create a cylinder of fleshy material from 1 to 3 feet in diameter and up to 10 feet long, allowing a passage to be made.\n\nThe material components are a pinch of earth and a drop of blood.\n\nThe reverse, flesh to stone, turns flesh of any sort to stone.\n\nAll possessions on the person of the creature likewise turn to stone.\n\nThe intended subject of the spell receives a saving throw vs.\n\nspell to avoid the effect.\n\nIf a statue created by this spell is subjected to breakage or weathering, the being (if ever returned to his original, fleshy state) will have similar damage, deformities, etc.\n\nThe DM may allow such damage to be repaired by various high-level clerical spells, such as regenerate.\n\nThe material components of the spell are lime, water, and earth.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 230,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 686,
      "name": "Superior Magnetism",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a small bar magnet",
      "range": "30 yds. + 5 yds./level",
      "aoe": "Special",
      "casting_time": "6",
      "duration": "1 rd./5 levels",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "2d6/level",
      "description": "When this spell is cast, the wizard designates one inanimate object of stone, earth, or metal within the spell's range to function as a powerful magnet, attracting all metal.\n\nThe object affected can be no larger than a 10-feet cube, although a section of wall, floor, or ceiling about 10 square feet will work.\n\nOnce magnetized, the object exerts a powerful attractive or repulsive force(caster's choice) against objects of ferrous metal.\n\nThe effects vary by the proximity of the metal objects to the center of magnetism, as shown below .See book for table.\n\nThe movement rate represent how fast objects are drawn to or repelled from the center of magnetism.\n\nIf the creature or object in question is heavier than the magnetized item, the magnetized item does the moving instead.\n\nThe effective strength is the pull of the magnetism at that range; the size equivalent refers to creature sizes, not weapons sizes.\n\nA character or creature carrying loose metal items or objects such as weapons, shields, helms, buttons, and so on must win opposed strength check (see player option: combat& tactics for information on opposed ability checks) in order to keep his possessions from being wrenched out of his grasp by the magnetism.\n\nSecuring a weapon in its sheath, holding an item with both hands, and other precautions may give the character a +2 to +4 to his base ability score, at the DM's discretion.\n\nCharacters wearing metal armor must attempt an opposed strength check to ignore the effects of the magnetism.\n\nIf the character fails his strength check outright, he loses his footing and flies towards or away from the object at the full rate indicated.\n\nHe suffers full falling damage based on the speed with which he hits the item- 1d6 for every 10 feet of the movement rate, or half that ground if the character passes his strength check but is beaten by the magnetism roll, he is moved one foot for each point he lost by.\n\nAgain, some precautions or assistance may help iron wearing characters in their strength checks.\n\nFor monsters, compare the creature's size to the effective size of magnetism.\n\nAn armored character who is stuck to a surface or object loses any dexterity adjustments to AC and cannot make any physical attacks.\n\nHe can try to wriggle out of his armor and free himself, employ a magical item, or use psionic powers if he has any at his disposal.\n\nThe material component for this spell is a small bar magnet, bent into a u-shape and coated with mithril.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 153,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 687,
      "name": "Tenser's Transformation",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a potion of heroism",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "The caster",
      "casting_time": "6",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "+2/level",
      "description": "Tenser's transformation is a sight guaranteed to astound any creature not aware of its power, for when the wizard casts the spell, he undergoes a startling transformation.\n\nThe size and strength of the wizard increase to heroic proportions, so he becomes a formidable fighting machine; the spell causes the caster to become a berserk fighter! The wizard's hit points double, and all damage he sustains comes first from the magical points gained; once these points are eliminated, all subsequent damage (to his true hit points) is doubled.\n\nThe AC of the wizard is 4 better than that possessed prior to casting the spell (AC 10 goes to 14, AC 11 to 15, AC 12 to 16, etc.), to a maximum Armor Class of 30 All attacks are as a fighter of the same level as the wizard (i.e., the wizard uses the combat values normally reserved for fighters).\n\nThe wizard can use either a dagger or a staff when attacking.\n\nA dagger can be used twice per round, and each successful attack inflicts an additional 2 points of damage.\n\nA staff can be used only once per round, but with a +2 bonus to attack and damage rolls.\n\nThe wizard fights in melee in preference to all other forms of attack, and continues attacking until all opponents are slain, he is killed, the magic is dispelled, or the spell duration expires.\n\nThe material component for casting this spell is a potion of heroism (or superheroism)that the wizard must consume during the course of uttering the spell.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 231,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 688,
      "name": "Transmute Water to Dust",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a pinch of normal dust",
      "range": "60 yds.",
      "aoe": "10-ft. cube/level",
      "casting_time": "5",
      "duration": "Permanent",
      "save": "1/2",
      "damage": "1d6/level",
      "description": "When this spell is cast, the subject area instantly undergoes a change from liquid to powdery dust.\n\nNote that if the water is already muddy, the area of effect is doubled, while if wet mud is being transmuted, the area of effect is quadrupled.\n\nIf water remains in contact with the transmuted dust, the former quickly soaks the latter, turning the dust into silty mud (if a sufficient quantity of water exists to do so), otherwise soaking or dampening the dust accordingly.\n\nOnly liquid actually in the area of effect at the moment of spellcasting is affected.\n\nLiquids that are only partially water are affected only insofar as the actual water content is concerned; however, potions containing water are rendered useless.\n\nLiving creatures are unaffected, except for those native to the Elemental Plane of Water.\n\nSuch creatures receive saving throws vs.\n\nspell.\n\nFailure inflicts 1d6 points of damage per caster level upon the subject, while success means the creature receives half damage.\n\nOnly one such creature can be affected by any single casting of this spell, regardless of the creature's size or the size of the spell's area of effect.\n\nThe reverse of the spell is simply a very high-powered create water spell that requires a pinch of normal dust as an additional material component.\n\nFor either usage of the spell, other components required are diamond dust of at least 500 gp value and a bit of seashell.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 231,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 689,
      "name": "Trollish Fortitude",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Necromancy",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a shred of dried flesh",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "The caster",
      "casting_time": "6",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "This powerful spell imbues the caster with the physical fortitude and resilience of a troll.\n\nWhile the spell is in effect, the caster regenerates 3 hit points per round until he reaches his normal maximum.\n\nHe also gains a troll's ability to ignore dismemberment, decapitation, and other horrible injures that would normally incapacitate or kill him (although losing a limb may prevent the caster from taking certain action, such as running, climbing, and other activities) breeding, wounding, being reduced to negative hit points, and other effects that cause the victim to lose hit points from round to round are ignored-the caster instead regains 3 hit points per round, up to his normal maximum.\n\nIf the caster is reduced to less than 0 hit points, he is incapacitated and must make a system shock roll or lose all of his highest level spells.\n\nThe incapacitation lasts only until his regeneration restores him to 1 hit point or more; he can move fight, and cast spells again as soon as his hit point total is positive.\n\nTrollish fortitude does not provide the caster with any defenses against lethal position, disease, and other effects level draining, vampiric touch, or vampiric regeneration cannot be regenerated since this represents damage to the victim's life force and not physical injury.\n\nIn addition, fire damage and acid damage cannot be regenerated.\n\nWhile the spell is in effect, the caster can rejoin severed limbs simply by holding them in place, but if the spell ends while a limb(which were already moving toward him) is still separate from his body, he immediately suffers the full effects of the injury.\n\nThe material component for this spell is a shred of dried flesh from a troll's heart that must be pulverized into dust.\n\nThe dust is then sprinkled on the caster.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 154,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 690,
      "name": "True Seeing",
      "level": "6",
      "school": "Divination",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "ointment",
      "range": "Touch",
      "aoe": "Line of sight,max. 60 ft.",
      "casting_time": "1 rd.",
      "duration": "1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When the wizard employs this spell, he confers upon the recipient the ability to see all things as they actually are.\n\nThe spell penetrates normal and magical darkness.\n\nSecret doors become plain.\n\nThe exact location of displaced things is obvious.\n\nInvisible things become visible.\n\nIllusions and apparitions are seen through.\n\nPolymorphed, changed, or enchanted objects are apparent.\n\n(The real form appears translucently superimposed on the apparent form: A gold dragon polymorphed to human form would appear human with a ghostly dragon looming over the human form.) Unlike the clerical version of this spell, the recipient cannot determine alignment.\n\nThe recipient can focus his vision to see into the Ethereal Plane or the bordering areas of adjacent planes.\n\nThe range of vision conferred is 60 feet.\n\nTrue seeing does not penetrate solid objects; it in no way confers Xray vision or its equivalent.\n\nFurthermore, the spell effects cannot be enhanced with magic.\n\nThe spell requires an ointment for the eyes that is made from a very rare mushroom powder, saffron, and fat.\n\nIt costs no less than 300gp per use and must be aged for 1d6 months.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 231,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
