    },
    {
      "id": 701,
      "name": "Descent into Madness",
      "level": "7",
      "school": "Enchantment",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a special cube of gold wire",
      "range": "10 yds./level",
      "aoe": "1 creature",
      "casting_time": "7",
      "duration": "Permanent",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "More insidious and powerful than the feeblemind spell, descent into madness afflicts one creature with a random form of insanity.\n\nThe spell can affect any creature with an Intelligence of low (5) or higher; however, a character or creature protected by a mind blank is immune to this spell.\n\nCreatures are entitled to a normal saving throw vs.\n\nspell to withstand the spell.\n\nThe form of insanity caused by the spell is determined by a roll on the chart: See chart for table.\n\nThe various types of insanity and their game effects are described under the Alienist in Chapter 6.\n\nThe caster has no idea what kind of madness the spell inflicts on its victim, although he may be able to form an educated guess after observing the victim for a few rounds.\n\nDescent into madness accelerates the process of insanity radically, producing an advanced condition almost immediately; for example, a character rendered paranoid by this spell skips past suspicion and instantly regards his friends and allies as enemies of the worst sort.\n\nThe victim has a small chance of recovering with the passage of time (as described under each type of insanity) but other than that the only ways to repair the effects of this spell are restoration, wish, or use of the psionic power psychic surgery.\n\nThe material component is a special cube of gold wire worth at least 500 gold pieces shaped to represent a tesseract, or four-dimensional figure.",
      "source": "Spells and Magic",
      "page": 154,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 702,
      "name": "Drawmij's Instant Summons",
      "level": "7",
      "school": "Conjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "a gem of not",
      "range": "Infinite + special",
      "aoe": "1 small object",
      "casting_time": "1",
      "duration": "Instantaneous",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "When this spell is cast, the wizard teleports some desired item from virtually any location directly to his hand.\n\nThe single object can be no longer in any dimension than a sword, can have no more weight than a shield (about eight pounds), and must be nonliving.\n\nTo prepare this spell, the wizard must hold a gem of not less than 5,000gp value in his hand and utter all but the final word of the conjuration.\n\nAt some point in the future, he must crush the gem and utter the final word.\n\nThe desired item is then transported instantly into the spellcaster's right or left hand, as he desires.\n\nThe item must have been previously touched during the initial incantation and specifically named; only that particular item is summoned by the spell.\n\nDuring the initial incantation, the gem becomes magically inscribed with the name of the item to be summoned.\n\nThe inscription is invisible and unreadable, except by means of a read magic spell, to all but the wizard who cast the summons.\n\nIf the item is in the possession of another creature, the spell does not work, and the caster knows who the possessor is and roughly where he, she, or it is located when the summons is cast.\n\nItems can be summoned from other planes of existence, but only if such items are not in the possession (not necessarily the physical grasp) of another creature.\n\nFor each level of experience above the 14th, the wizard is able to summon a desired item from one plane farther removed from the plane he is in at the time the spell is cast (one plane away at 14th level, two planes away at 15th, etc.).\n\nThus, a wizard of 16th level could cast the spell even if the desired item was on the second layer of one of the Outer Planes, but at 14th level the wizard would be able to summon the item only if it were no farther than one of the Inner Planes, the Ethereal Plane, or the Astral Plane (see the Planescape Campaign Setting boxed set).\n\nNote that special wards or barriers, or factors that block the teleport or plane shift spells, may also block the operation of this spell.\n\nObjects in Leomund's secret chest cannot be recovered by using this spell.\n\nNote: If the item is wizard marked, it can be summoned from anywhere on the same plane unless special local conditions apply.\n\nFurthermore, the details of the location of the item are more specific, and the item is more easily traceable with other types of scrying magic.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 233,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 703,
      "name": "Duo-Dimension",
      "level": "7",
      "school": "Alteration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": true,
      "materials": "flat ivory",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "The caster",
      "casting_time": "7",
      "duration": "3 rds. + 1 rd./level",
      "save": "None",
      "damage": "2d4/level",
      "description": "A duo-dimension spell causes the caster to have only two dimensions, height and width, with no depth.\n\nHe is thus invisible when turned sideways.\n\nThis invisibility can be detected only by means of a true seeing spell or similar methods.\n\nIn addition, the duodimensional wizard can pass through the thinnest of spaces as long as these have the proper height--going through the space between a door and its frame is a simple matter.\n\nThe wizard can perform all actions normally.\n\nHe can turn and become invisible, move in this state, and appear again next round and cast a spell, disappearing on the following round.\n\nNote that when turned, the wizard cannot be affected by any form of attack, but when visible, he is subject to double the amount of damage normal for an attack form; for example, a dagger thrust would inflict 2d4 points of damage if it struck a duodimensional wizard.\n\nFurthermore, the wizard has a portion of his existence in the Astral Plane when the spell is in effect, and he is subject to possible notice by creatures there.\n\nIf noticed, it is 25% probable that the wizard is pulled entirely into the Astral Plane by any attack from an astral creature.\n\nSuch an attack (and any subsequent attack received on the Astral Plane) inflicts normal damage.\n\nThe material components of this spell are a flat ivory likeness of the spellcaster (which must be of finest workmanship, gold filigreed, and enamelled and gem-studded at an average cost of 500 to 1,000gp) and a strip of parchment.\n\nAs the spell is uttered, the parchment is given half a twist and joined at the ends.\n\nThe figurine is then passed through the parchment loop, and both disappear forever.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 233,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 704,
      "name": "Finger of Death",
      "level": "7",
      "school": "Necromancy",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "60 yds.",
      "aoe": "1 creature",
      "casting_time": "5",
      "duration": "Permanent",
      "save": "Negate",
      "damage": "2d8+1/level",
      "description": "The finger of death spell snuffs out the victim's life force.\n\nIf successful, the victim can be neither raised nor resurrected.\n\nIn addition, in human subjects the spell initiates changes to the body such that after three days the caster can, by means of a special ceremony costing not less than 1,000gp plus 500gp per body, animate the corpse as a juju zombie under the control of the caster.\n\nThe changes can be reversed before animation by a limited wish or similar spell cast directly upon the body, and a full wish restores the subject to life.\n\nThe caster utters the finger of death spell incantation, points his index finger at the creature to be slain, and unless the victim succeeds in a saving throw vs.\n\nspell, death occurs.\n\nA creature successfully saving still receives 2d8+1 points of damage.\n\nIf the subject dies of damage, no internal changes occur and the victim can then be revived normally.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 233,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 705,
      "name": "Forcecage",
      "level": "7",
      "school": "Evocation",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
