      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "10 yds.",
      "aoe": "4 ft./level wide  x 2 ft./level high",
      "casting_time": "7",
      "duration": "1 turn/level",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** enables the wizard to conjure a vertical, opaque wall--a shimmering,multicolored plane of light that protects him from all forms of attack.\n\nThe wall flashes with all colors of the visible spectrum, seven of which have a distinct power and purpose.The wall is immobile, and the spellcaster can pass through the wall without harm.\n\nHowever, any creature with fewer than 8 Hit Dice that is within 20 feet of the wall and does not shield its vision is blinded for 2d4 rounds by the colors.Each color in the wall has a special effect.\n\nEach color can also be negated by a specific magical effect, but the colors must be negated in the precise order of the spectrum.\n\nThe accompanying table shows the seven colors of the wall, the order in which they appear,their effects on creatures trying to attack the spellcaster, and the magic needed to negate each color.The wall's maximum proportions are 4 feet wide per level of experience of the caster and 2 feet high per level of experience.\n\nA prismatic wall spell cast to materialize in a space occupied by a creature is disrupted and the spell is wasted.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 243,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 759,
      "name": "Screen",
      "level": "8",
      "school": "Abjuration",
      "caster": "wizard",
      "verbal": true,
      "somatic": true,
      "material": false,
      "materials": "",
      "range": "0",
      "aoe": "30-ft. cube/level",
      "casting_time": "1 turn",
      "duration": "1 hr./level",
      "save": "Special",
      "damage": "",
      "description": "**This spell** combines several elements to create a powerful protection from scrying and direct observation.\n\nWhen the spell is cast, the wizard dictates what will and will not be observed in the area of effect.\n\nThe illusion created must be stated in general terms.\n\nThus, the caster could specify the illusion of him and another playing chess for the duration of the spell, but he could not have the illusionary chess players take a break, make dinner,and then resume their game.\n\nHe could have a crossroads appear quiet and empty even while an army is actually passing through the area.\n\nHe could specify that no one be seen (including passing strangers), that his troops be undetected, or even that every fifth man or unit should be visible.\n\nOnce the conditions are set, they cannot be changed.\n\nAttempts to scry the area automatically detect the image stated by the caster with no saving throw allowed.\n\nSight and sound are appropriate to the illusion created.\n\nA band of men standing in a meadow could be concealed as an empty meadow with birds chirping, etc.\n\nDirect observation may allow a saving throw (as per a normal illusion), if there is cause to disbelieve what is seen.\n\nCertainly onlookers in the area would become suspicious if the column of a marching army disappeared at one point to reappear at another! Even entering the area does not cancel the illusion or necessarily allow a saving throw, assuming the hidden beings take care to stay out of the way of those affected by the illusion.",
      "source": "Player's Handbook",
      "page": 243,
      "reversible": false
    },
    {
      "id": 760,
      "name": "Serten's Spell Immunity",
      "level": "8",
